ugust 2016 |script-title= ru:\u041a\u0430\u0431\u043c\u0438\u043d \u0443\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b|publisher= bigmir.net |language= ru |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160802190844/http://finance.bigmir.net/budget/72072-Kabmin-utverdil-novye-zarplaty-dlja-Poroshenko-i-Grojsmana |archivedate= 2 August 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| office4 = [[People's Deputy of Ukraine]]\n| convocation4 = [[3rd Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|3rd convocation]]\n| constituency4 = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]], [[Vinnytsia Oblast]],<br />[[Vinnytsia II (single-mandate constituency)|District No.12]]<ref>{{cite web|title=People's Deputy of Ukraine of the III convocation|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/d_ank_arh?kod=212303|website=Official portal|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|accessdate=22 December 2014|language=Ukrainian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405083801/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/d_ank_arh?kod=212303|archivedate=5 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| term_start4 = 12 May 1998\n| term_end4 = 14 May 2002\n| convocation5 = [[4th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|4th convocation]]\n| constituency5 = [[Our Ukraine\u2013People's Self-Defense Bloc|Our Ukraine Bloc]], [[Vinnytsia Oblast]], [[Vinnytsia II (single-mandate constituency)|District No.12]]<ref>{{cite web|title=People's Deputy of Ukraine of the IV convocation|url=http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/5|website=Official portal|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|accessdate=22 December 2014|language=Ukrainian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113164921/http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/5|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Registered candidates|url=http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vd2002/WEBPROC0V|website=Elections of the People's Deputies of Ukraine|publisher=[[Central Election Commission of Ukraine]]|accessdate=24 December 2014|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101083540/http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vd2002/WEBPROC0V|archivedate=1 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| term_start5 = 14 May 2003\n| term_end5 = 8 September 2006\n| convocation6 = [[5th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|5th convocation]]\n| constituency6 = [[Our Ukraine\u2013People's Self-Defense Bloc|Our Ukraine Bloc]], No.33<ref>{{cite web|title=People's Deputy of Ukraine of the V convocation|url=http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/6|website=Official portal|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|accessdate=22 December 2014|language=Ukrainian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608060139/http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/6|archivedate=8 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| term_start6 = 25 May 2006\n| term_end6 = 15 June 2007\n| convocation7 = [[7th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|7th convocation]]\n| successor7   = [[Oleksiy Poroshenko]]\n| constituency7 = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]], [[Vinnytsia Oblast]],<br />[[Vinnytsia II (single-mandate constituency)|District No.12]]<ref>{{cite web|title=People's Deputy of Ukraine of the VII convocation|url=http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/8|website=Official portal|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|accessdate=22 December 2014|language=Ukrainian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113164920/http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/2273/8|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| term_start7 = 12 December 2012\n| term_end7 = 3 June 2014\n}}\n\n'''Petro Oleksiyovych Poroshenko''' ({{lang-uk|\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0301 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0456\u0301\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u0301\u043d\u043a\u043e}}, {{IPA-uk|pe\u02c8tr\u0254 olek\u02c8s\u207d\u02b2\u207eijow\u026at\u0283 poro\u02c8\u0283\u025bnko|pron}}; born 26 September 1965<ref name=\"bio2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.president.gov.ua/en/president/petro-poroshenko |title=Petro Poroshenko\u2019s biography |accessdate=2019-01-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210185957/http://www.president.gov.ua/en/president/petro-poroshenko |archivedate=10 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) is a Ukrainian businessman and politician who served as the fifth [[President of Ukraine|President]] of [[Ukraine]] from 2014 to 2019.\n\nHe served as the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Ukraine)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 2009 to 2010, and as the [[Ministry of Economic Development and Trade (Ukraine)|Minister of Trade and Economic Development]] in 2012. From 2007 until 2012, Poroshenko headed the Council of [[National Bank of Ukraine|Ukraine's National Bank]].\n\nOutside government, Poroshenko has been a prominent [[Ukrainian oligarch]]<ref name=\"BBC Profile Poroshenko\">{{cite web|title=Profile: Ukraine's President Petro Poroshenko|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26822741|publisher=BBC|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=10 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526215821/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26822741|archivedate=26 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with a lucrative career in acquiring and building assets. His most recognized brands are [[Roshen]], the large-scale confectionery company which has earned him the nickname of \"Chocolate King\",<ref name=\"BBC Profile Poroshenko\"/> and the TV channel ''[[5 kanal]]'', an all-news national TV broadcaster. Due to the scale of his business holdings in the manufacturing, agriculture and financial sectors, his political influence that included several stints at government prior to his presidency, and ownership of an influential mass-media outlet, Poroshenko has long been considered one of the prominent Ukrainian oligarchs even though not the most influential among them.\n\nHe was [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|elected president on 25 May 2014]], capturing 54.7% of the vote in the first round, thereby winning outright and avoiding a run-off. As a candidate for a second term in [[2019 Ukrainian presidential election|2019]], he obtained only 24.5% in the second round, being defeated by [[Volodymyr Zelensky]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nPoroshenko's father, {{Interlanguage link|Oleksij Poroshenko|de|Oleksij Poroschenko|uk|\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0456\u0439 \u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|ru|\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|WD=}}, was an engineer and later government official who managed multiple factories during the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet rule in Ukraine]]. Little is known about his mother Yevguenia Sergu\u00e9ievna Grigorchuk (1937\u20132004) but a Ukrainian newspaper said she was an accountant, who taught at a vocational and technical school of accounting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vinbazar.com/news/nshe/mati-ta-starshii-brat-petra-porosa-trokhi-sa-na-nevidomi-storinki-biografiyi|script-title=uk:\u041c\u0430\u0442\u0456\u0440 \u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u0431\u0456\u043b\u0456 \u043f\u043b\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u0431\u0456\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0456\u0457 \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0431\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430|language=Ukrainian|date=5 June 2014|publisher=Vinbazar}}</ref> He also spent his childhood and youth in [[Bender, Moldova|Bendery]] ([[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]], now under ''de facto'' control of the unrecognized [[List of states with limited recognition|breakaway state]] [[Transnistria]]),<ref name=\"KPp71016\">[https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/540626.html All In The Family: The Sequel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129115129/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/540626.html |date=29 November 2016 }}, [[Kyiv Post]] (7 October 2016)</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Marcin Kosienkowski|url=https://www.academia.edu/1918412/Continuity_and_Change_in_Transnistrias_Foreign_Policy_after_the_2011_Presidential_Elections|title=Continuity and Change in Transnistria's Foreign Policy after the 2011 Presidential Elections|publisher=[[Academia.edu]]|date=2012|page=38}}</ref> where his father Oleksij was heading a machine building plant.<ref name=KPp71016/>\n\nIn his youth, Poroshenko practiced judo and [[Sambo (martial art)|sambo]], and was a [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|Candidate for Master of Sport of the USSR]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Despite good grades, he was not awarded the normal gold medal at graduation, and on his report card he was given a \"C\" for his behavior.<ref name=PpofileSO/> After getting into a fight with four [[Soviet Army]] cadets at the military commissariat, he was sent to army service in the distant [[Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic]].<ref name=PpofileSO/>\n\nIn 1989, Poroshenko graduated, having started studying in 1982, with a degree in economics from the international relations and law department (subsequently the Institute of International Relations) at the [[Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv|Kiev State University]].<ref name=\"ITAR\">{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/en/economy/733301 |title=Ukraine's tycoon Poroshenko confirms plans to sell assets |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia|ITAR-TASS]] |date=26 May 2014 |accessdate=26 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220635/http://en.itar-tass.com/economy/733301 |archivedate=27 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> At this university he was friends with [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] who he in May 2015 would appoint as [[Governor of Odessa Oblast|Governor]] of the [[Odessa Oblast]] (region) and who is a former [[President of Georgia]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150531021718/http://m.dw.de/ukrainian/mobile.A-18487589-9874.html Saakashvili took over as head of the Odessa Regional State Administration], [[Deutsche Welle]] (30 May 2015)</ref>\n\nIn 1984 Poroshenko married a medical student, Maryna Perevedentseva (born 1962).<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Their first son, Oleksiy, was born in 1985 ([[Oleksiy Poroshenko|his three other children were born in 2000 and 2001]]).<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nFrom 1989 to 1992 Poroshenko was an assistant at the university's international economic relations department.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> While still a student, he founded a legal advisory firm mediating the negotiation of contracts in foreign trade, and then he undertook the negotiations himself, starting to supply [[cocoa bean]]s to the Soviet chocolate industry in 1991.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> At the same time, he was deputy director of the 'Republic' Union of Small Businesses and Entrepreneurs, and the CEO \"Exchange House Ukraine\".<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nPoroshenko's brother, Mykhailo, older by eight years, died in a 1997 car accident under mysterious circumstances.<ref name=\"LIGA\">{{in lang|ru}}'''/(website has automatic [[Google Translate]] option)''' [http://file.liga.net/person/404-petr-poroshenko.html Short bio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305055205/http://file.liga.net/person/404-petr-poroshenko.html |date=5 March 2013 }}, LIGA</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nIn 1993, Poroshenko, together with his father Oleksiy and colleagues from the Road Traffic Institute in Kiev, created the UkrPromInvest Ukrainian Industry and Investment Company, which specialized in the confectionery and automotive industries (as well as in other agricultural processing later on.)<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Poroshenko was director-general of the company from its founding until 1998, when in connection with his entry into parliament he handed the title over to his father, while retaining the title of honorary president.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nBetween 1996 and 1998, UkrPromInvest acquired control over several state-owned confectionery enterprises which were combined into the [[Roshen]] group in 1996, creating the largest confectionery manufacturing operation in [[Ukraine]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> His business success in this industry earned him the nickname \"Chocolate King\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Abram Brown |date=31 March 2014 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2014/03/31/the-willy-wonka-of-ukraine-is-now-the-leading-presidential-candidate/ |title=The Willy Wonka of Ukraine Is Now The Leading Presidential Candidate |journal=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=19 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2014/03/31/the-willy-wonka-of-ukraine-is-now-the-leading-presidential-candidate/ |archivedate=1 December 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko's business empire also includes several car and bus factories, [[Kuznya na Rybalskomu]] shipyard, the [[5 Kanal (Ukraine)|5 Kanal]] television channel,<ref name=\"poro5\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/67473/ |title=Poroshenko is not going to sell Channel 5 TV |work=Kyiv Post |date=23 May 2010 |accessdate=25 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525042142/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/67473/ |archivedate=25 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> as well as other businesses in Ukraine.\n\nAlthough not the most prominent in the list of his business holdings, the assets that drew much recent media attention, and often controversy, are the confectionery factory in [[Lipetsk]], Russia, that became controversial due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)]], the [[Sevastopol Marine Plant]] (Sevmorzavod) that has been confiscated after the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|2014 Russian forcible annexation of Crimea]] and the media outlet [[5 kanal]], particularly because of Poroshenko's repeated refusal to sell an influential media asset following his accession to presidency.\n\nAccording to Poroshenko (and [[Rothschild & Co|Rothschild Wealth Management & Trust]]) since becoming President of Ukraine he has relinquished the management of his businesses, ultimately (in January 2016) to a [[blind trust]].<ref name=KPp71016/><ref name=\"Pbt20117b\">[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/397675.html Roshen quits activity of its factory in Lipetsk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120130300/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/397675.html |date=20 January 2017 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 January 2017)</ref>\n\n=== Billionaires lists rankings===\nIn March 2012, ''[[Forbes]]'' placed him on the [[Forbes list of billionaires (2012)|Forbes list of billionaires]] at 1,153rd place, with $1&nbsp;billion USD.<ref>{{cite news|date=8 March 2012 |accessdate=8 March 2012 |author=Brian Bonner |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/123875/ |title=Eight Ukrainians make Forbes magazine's list of world billionaires |newspaper=[[Kyiv Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/123875/ |archivedate=1 December 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> As of May 2015, Poroshenko's net worth was about $720&nbsp;million USD ([[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] estimate), losing 25 percent of his wealth because of Russia's ban of Roshen products and the state of the Ukrainian economy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billionaire No More: Ukraine President's Fortune Fades With War|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-08/billionaire-no-more-ukraine-president-s-fortune-fades-with-war|newspaper=Bloomberg Business|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=22 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526063035/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-08/billionaire-no-more-ukraine-president-s-fortune-fades-with-war|archivedate=26 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the annual ranking of the richest people in Ukraine<ref name=\"NV201510\">{{cite web|author=Vitaliy Sych|url=http://nv.ua/opinion/sych/poroshenko-rastet-ahmetov-padaet---svezhij-top-100-samyh-bogatyh-ukraintsev-77166.html|script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0442, \u0410\u0445\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u2013 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0439 \u0422\u043e\u043f-100 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0431\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0445 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432|trans-title=Poroshenko grows, Akhmetov falls \u2013 Fresh Top 100 richest Ukrainians|language=ru|publisher=Novoe Vremia|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=10 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311074035/http://nv.ua/opinion/sych/poroshenko-rastet-ahmetov-padaet---svezhij-top-100-samyh-bogatyh-ukraintsev-77166.html|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> published by the Ukrainian journal [[Novoye Vremya (journal and site)|Novoye Vremya]] and conducted jointly with [[Dragon Capital (Ukraine)|Dragon Capital]], a leading investment company in Ukraine, published in October 2015, president Poroshenko was found to be the only one from the top ten list whose asset value grew since the previous year's ranking. The estimate of his assets was set at $979 million USD, a 20% growth, and his ranking increased from 9th to 6th wealthiest person in Ukraine. The article noted that Poroshenko remained one of the only two European leaders who owned a business empire of such scale, with [[Silvio Berlusconi]] of Italy being the other.\n\nA total of \u20ac450 million is kept in an Amsterdam-based company registered in Cyprus, as a result of which his effective tax rate is 5% rather than the statutory tax rate of 18% in Ukraine. The company is likely to be worth much more, as the annual accounts published by the Dutch Chamber of Commerce only contain the book value of the shares, which is very likely to be lower than the market value.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alle schimmige geldstromen belastingontwijkende President Oekra\u00efne in \u00e9\u00e9n handig overzicht|url=http://925.nl/archief/2016/11/24/handig-alle-schimmige-geldstromen-belastingontwijkende-president-oekraine-in-een-overzicht/|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=9 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415135655/http://925.nl/archief/2016/11/24/handig-alle-schimmige-geldstromen-belastingontwijkende-president-oekraine-in-een-overzicht/|archivedate=15 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After his election, Poroshenko lost the billionaire status as his net worth dropped by 40% to reach $705 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10556442-poroshenko-lost-billionaire-status-during-presidency-media.html|title=Poroshenko lost billionaire status during presidency \u2013 media|date=20 May 2019|website=unian.info|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n\n===Associated businesses===\nA number of businesses were once part of the {{ill|Ukrprominvest|uk|\u0413\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0430 \u00ab\u0423\u043a\u0440\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u00bb|vertical-align=sup}} which Poroshenko headed in 1993\u20131998. The investment group was dissolved in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economics.unian.ua/industry/640677-kontsern-ukrprominvest-ogolosiv-pro-likvidatsiyu.html |script-title=uk:\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u043d \"\u0423\u043a\u0440\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\" \u043e\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044e |trans-title=Concern \"Ukrprominvest\" announced its liquidation |agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]] |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=1 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://economics.unian.ua/industry/640677-kontsern-ukrprominvest-ogolosiv-pro-likvidatsiyu.html |language=uk |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko has stated that upon beginning his political activity he passed on his holdings to a trust fund.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\n*[[Bogdan group]] (Poroshenko sold his share in connection with the collapse of its production after the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]] in 2009),<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> centered in [[Cherkasy]]\n*[[Roshen]] group\n*[[5 Kanal (Ukraine)|5 Kanal]] and [[Pryamiy kanal|Pryamiy]] television channels (he denies property relations with Pryamiy<ref>{{cite web|title=Poroshenko says attempts underway to raid Pryamiy TV, denies ties with channel|url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/606720.html|website=News Agency|publisher=Interfax|accessdate=15 August 2019|language=English}}</ref>).\n*[[Kuznya na Rybalskomu]] shipyard<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> in [[Kiev]]\n*International Invest Bank,<ref>Komakha, O. [https://web.archive.org/web/20171130021907/http://minprom.ua/articles/167144.html \"The Poroshenko's Bank is growing in 10 times faster (\u0411\u0430\u043d\u043a \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0432 10 \u0440\u0430\u0437 \u0431\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0435)\"]. Minprom Information Agency. 16 October 2014</ref> owned through a trust and along with [[Ihor Kononenko]]\n*Ukrprominvest-Agro, an agrarian holding\n**[[Zorya Podillya]], an agrarian company near [[Haisyn]], specializing in sugar production from [[sugar beet]]s\n**Podillya\n**MAS-Agro\n**Ahrofirma \"Dniproahrolan\"\n**Ahrofirma \"Ivankivtsi\"\n* [[Sevastopol Shipyard]] (lost in 2015 due to a [[corporate raid]] by the Russian occupational authorities in Crimea)\n\n==Early political career==\nPoroshenko first won a seat in the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (the Ukrainian Parliament) [[1998 Ukrainian parliamentary election|in 1998]] for the [[Vinnytsia II (single-mandate constituency)|12th single-mandate constituency]]. He was initially a member of the [[United Social Democratic Party of Ukraine]] (SDPU), the party led by [[Viktor Medvedchuk]] and loyal to president [[Leonid Kuchma]] at the time.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Poroshenko left SDPU(o) in 2000 to create an independent [[Left-wing politics|left]]-of-[[Centrism|center]] faction and then a party, naming it [[Solidarity (Ukraine)|Party of Ukraine's Solidarity]] (PSU).<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/><ref name=\"TKSolPor\">{{cite web|format=PDF|author-link1=Taras Kuzio|author1=Kuzio, Taras|author2=Frishberg, Alex|url=http://www.taraskuzio.net/legal_files/Frishberg_Feb.08.pdf|title=Ukrainian Political Update|date=21 February 2008|work=Frishberg & Partners, Attorneys at Law|page=22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303173602/http://www.taraskuzio.net/legal_files/Frishberg_Feb.08.pdf|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2001 Poroshenko was instrumental in creating the [[Party of Regions]], also loyal to Kuchma; the Party of Ukraine's Solidarity having merged into the Party of Regions, Poroshenko launched a new party with a similar name, the party \"[[Solidarity (Ukraine)|Solidarity]].<ref name=PoroWP/>\n\n==Secretary of the National Security and Defense Council==\n[[File:Mukacheve 2004 Yushchenko and Baloha.JPG|thumb|left|Poroshenko and [[Viktor Yushchenko]] during the meeting before [[Mukacheve]] mayoral election on 16 April 2004.]]\n\nIn December 2001, Poroshenko broke ranks with Kuchma supporters to become campaign chief of [[Viktor Yushchenko]]'s [[Our Ukraine Bloc]] opposition faction. After [[2002 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections in March 2002]] in which Our Ukraine won the biggest share of the popular vote and Poroshenko won a seat in parliament,<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=23 June 2010|url=http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vd2002/webproc0e|title=Results of voting in single-mandate constituencies|publisher=[[Central Election Commission of Ukraine]]}}{{Dead link|date=March 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Poroshenko served as head of the parliamentary budget committee, where he was accused of \"misplacing 47&nbsp;million hryvnias\" (USD$8.9&nbsp;million).<ref name=\"Book\">{{cite book|author=Freedom House|title=Nations in Transit 2004: Democratization in East Central Europe and Eurasia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AsJlnVU4ipoC&pg=PA638|date=2004|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4617-3141-2|pages=638\u2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113164920/https://books.google.com/books?id=AsJlnVU4ipoC&pg=PA638|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a consequence of Poroshenko's Our Ukraine Bloc membership tax inspectors launched an attack on his business.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Despite great difficulties, UkrPromInvest managed to survive until Yushchenko became [[President of Ukraine]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nPoroshenko was considered a close confidant of Yushchenko, who is the godfather of Poroshenko's daughters. Poroshenko was likely the wealthiest oligarch<ref name=\"BBC Profile Poroshenko\"/> among Yushchenko supporters, and was often named as one of the main financial backers of Our Ukraine and the [[Orange Revolution]].<ref name=\"Support\">{{cite web|date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=26 May 2014 |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/politics/op-ed-petro-poroshenko-the-oligarch-poised-to-become-ukraine-president/article/384617 |title=Op-Ed: Petro Poroshenko the oligarch poised to become Ukraine president |work=Digital Journal |last=Hanly |first=Ken |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527181527/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/politics/op-ed-petro-poroshenko-the-oligarch-poised-to-become-ukraine-president/article/384617 |archivedate=27 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> After Yushchenko won the [[2004 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential elections in 2004]], Poroshenko was appointed Secretary of the [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|National Security and Defense Council]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/><ref name=\"ITAR\" />\n[[File:Petro Poroshenko (2005 ).jpg|thumb|Poroshenko attending a U.S. Independence Day celebration at the [[Embassy of the United States, Kiev|U.S. Embassy in Kiev]], 6 July 2005.]]\nIn September 2005, highly publicized mutual allegations of corruption erupted between Poroshenko and Prime Minister [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] involving the privatizations of state-owned firms.<ref name=PoroGUOCKP/> Poroshenko, for example, was accused of defending the interests of [[Viktor Pinchuk]], who had acquired state firm Nikopol Ferroalloy for $80&nbsp;million, independently valued at $1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-09-27/news/0509270090_1_petro-poroshenko-privatization-ukrainians |title=In Ukraine, old whiff of scandal in new regime |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=27 September 2005 |author=Alex Rodriguez |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002143944/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-09-27/news/0509270090_1_petro-poroshenko-privatization-Ukrainians |archivedate=2 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\nIn response to the allegations, Yushchenko dismissed his entire [[Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine|cabinet of ministers]], including Poroshenko and Tymoshenko.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite news |url=http://files.korrespondent.net/persons/poroshenko |language=ru |title=Biography |publisher=[[Korrespondent.net]] |url-status=dead |archivedate=19 July 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719091220/http://files.korrespondent.net/politics/poroshenko/ |df=dmy }}</ref> State prosecutors dismissed an abuse of power investigation against Poroshenko the following month,<ref>{{cite news|title=Prosecutors Close Criminal Case Against Yushchenko's Close Ally|url=http://news.kievukraine.info/2005/10/prosecutors-close-criminal-case.html|date=21 October 2005|publisher=Kiev Ukraine News Blog|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407082558/http://news.kievukraine.info/2005/10/prosecutors-close-criminal-case.html|archivedate=7 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> immediately after Yushchenko dismissed [[Svyatoslav Piskun]], [[General Prosecutor of Ukraine]]. Piskun claimed that he was sacked because he refused to institute criminal proceedings against Tymoshenko and refused to drop proceedings against Poroshenko.<ref>{{cite web |date=28 October 2005 |accessdate=3 March 2012 |url=http://en.for-ua.com/analytics/2005/10/28/164030.html |title=Independent standpoint on Ukraine:Dismissal of Prosecutor-General, Closure of Poroshenko Case Create New |author=Tammy M. Lynch |publisher=ForUm |archivedate=3 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103105813/http://en.for-ua.com/analytics/2005/10/28/164030.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2006 Ukrainian parliamentary election|March 2006 parliamentary election]], Poroshenko was re-elected to the [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] with the support of [[Our Ukraine\u2013People's Self-Defense Bloc|Our Ukraine]] electoral bloc.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> He chaired the parliamentary Committee on Finance and Banking. Allegedly, since Poroshenko claimed the post of [[Chairman of the Ukrainian Parliament]] for himself, the [[Socialist Party of Ukraine]] chose to be part of the [[Alliance of National Unity]] because it was promised that their party leader, [[Oleksandr Moroz]], would be elected chairman if the coalition were formed.<ref name=bio/> This left Poroshenko's Our Ukraine and their ally [[Yulia Tymoshenko Bloc]] out of the [[Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine|Government]].\n\nPoroshenko did not run in the [[2007 Ukrainian parliamentary election|September 2007 parliamentary election]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Poroshenko started heading the Council of [[National Bank of Ukraine|Ukraine's National Bank]] in February 2007.<ref name=bio/><ref name=\"KP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/50277/ |title=Regions Party not to vote for Poroshenko's appointment Ukraine's foreign minister |work=[[Kyiv Post]] |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=8 October 2009 |accessdate=8 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archivedate=5 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605175033/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/50277/ |df=dmy }}</ref> Between 1999 and 2012 he was a board member of the National Bank of Ukraine.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\n==Foreign Minister and Minister of Trade==\n[[File:Yulia Tymoshenko November 2009-4.jpeg|thumb|Poroshenko at the Russian-Ukrainian international commission meeting in 2009.]]\n[[File:George Papandreou and Petro Poroshenko 2009.jpg|left|thumb|Minister for Foreign Affairs of Ukraine Petro Poroshenko in the Polish Senate with former Greek prime minister [[George Papandreou]].]]\nUkrainian President [[Yushchenko]] nominated Poroshenko for [[Foreign Minister of Ukraine|Foreign Minister]] on 7 October 2009.<ref name=\"KP\"/><ref name=\"IF\">{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/21575.html|title=Ukrainian president proposes Petro Poroshenko for foreign minister|agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]]|date=7 October 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311072531/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/21575.html|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Poroshenko was appointed by the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (Ukraine's parliament) on 9 October 2009.<ref name=\"new\">{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/21692/ |title=Rada appoints Poroshenko Ukraine's foreign minister |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=9 October 2009 |accessdate=5 December 2009 |archivedate=23 May 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523175756/http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/21575/ |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>By 240 out of 440 MPs registered in the session hall. In particular, 151 MPs of the [[Bloc of Yulia Tymoshenko]] faction, 63 of the [[Our Ukraine-People's Self-Defense Bloc]], 20 members of the [[Bloc of Volodymyr Lytvyn]], one deputy of the [[Party of Regions]], one member of the [[Communist Party of Ukraine|Communist Party]] faction, and four deputies not belonging to any faction voted for the nomination.</ref> On 12 October 2009, President Yushchenko re-appointed Poroshenko to the National Security and Defense Council.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/poroshenko-put-on-ukraines-nscd-50528.html |title=Poroshenko put on Ukraine's NSCD |work=[[Kyiv Post]] |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=12 October 2009 |url-status=live |archivedate=19 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419153310/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/poroshenko-put-on-ukraines-nscd-50528.html |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko supported [[NATO-Ukrainian relations|Ukrainian NATO-membership]]. However, he also stated [[Enlargement of NATO|NATO membership]] should not be a goal in itself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/54359/ |title=Poroshenko: Ukraine could join NATO in 1\u20132 years, with political, public will |work=Kyiv Post |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=4 December 2009 |accessdate=5 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130215152/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/54359/ |archivedate=30 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Although Poroshenko was dismissed as foreign minister on 11 March 2010, President [[Viktor Yanukovych]] expressed hope for further cooperation with him.<ref name=poro5/>\n\nIn late February 2012, Poroshenko was named as the new [[Ministry of Economic Development and Trade (Ukraine)|Minister of Trade and Economic Development]] in the [[Azarov Government]];<ref>{{cite news|date=23 February 2012 |accessdate=9 March 2012 |url=http://www.unian.info/politics/612959-mass-media-poroshenko-heads-ministry-of-economy.html |title=Mass Media:Poroshenko heads Ministry of Economy |agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]] |archivedate=24 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224153502/http://www.unian.net/eng/news/487680-mass-media-poroshenko-heads-ministry-of-economy.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=23 February 2012 |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/122996/ |title=Regions Party: Poroshenko appointed economy minister, Kolobov appointed finance minister |work=Kyiv Post |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |accessdate=9 March 2012 |archivedate=9 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309085122/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/122996/ |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/23085.html |title=President:Prime Minister nominated Petro Poroshenko for Minister of Economy |publisher=[[President.gov.ua]] |date=23 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128000855/http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/23085.html |archivedate=28 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> on 9 March 2012, President Yanukovych stated he wanted Poroshenko to work in the government in the post of economic development and trade minister.<ref>{{cite news|date=9 March 2012 |accessdate=9 March 2012 |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123980/ |title=Ukrainian president wants Poroshenko to head economic development and trade ministry |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |work=[[Kyiv Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309162724/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/123980/ |archivedate=9 March 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> On 23 March 2012, Poroshenko was appointed economic development and trade minister of Ukraine by Yanukovych.<ref name=\"trademinis\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124833/ |title=Poroshenko appointed economic development and trade minister of Ukraine|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|agency=Interfax-Ukraine|accessdate=23 March 2012|date=23 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124833/|archivedate=1 December 2008}}<br />{{cite news|date=23 March 2012|accessdate=23 March 2012|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124844/|title=Poroshenko explains reasons behind accepting economy minister's post|work=[[Kyiv Post]]|agency=Interfax-Ukraine|archivedate=23 March 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323190901/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/124844/}}</ref> The same month he stepped down as head of the Council of [[National Bank of Ukraine|Ukraine's National Bank]].<ref name=\"LigaPPorsh\">{{cite web|publisher=LIGA.net |url=http://file.liga.net/person/404-petr-poroshenko.html |script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 |trans-title=Petr Aleksiyovych Poroshenko |accessdate=20 February 2013 |archivedate=5 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305055205/http://file.liga.net/person/404-petr-poroshenko.html |language=ru |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPoroshenko claims that he became Minister of Trade and Economic Development in order to help bring [[Ukraine\u2013European Union relations|Ukraine closer to the EU]] and get Yulia Tymoshenko [[Criminal cases against Yulia Tymoshenko since 2010|released from prison]].<ref name=PpofileSO/> After he took the post, tax inspectors launched an attack on his business.<ref name=PpofileSO/>\n\n==Return to parliament==\nPoroshenko returned to the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (parliament) after the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election]] after winning (with more than 70%) as an independent candidate in [[single-member districts|single-member district]] number 12 ([[first-past-the-post]] wins a parliamentary seat) located in [[Vinnytsia Oblast]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.rbc.ua/rus/vyboru2012/person/o101 Candidates single-mandate constituency \u2116 12] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605053136/http://www.rbc.ua/rus/vyboru2012/person/o101 |date=5 June 2014 }}, [[RBC Ukraine]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vnd2012/WP040?PT001F01=900&pf7331=12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221141512/http://www.cvk.gov.ua/pls/vnd2012/WP040?PT001F01=900&pf7331=12|archivedate=21 February 2014|script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. \u041e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \u2116112|trans-title=Vinnytsia region. The single-mandate constituency \u2116 12|publisher=[[Central Election Commission of Ukraine]]|language=uk|df=dmy-all|access-date=14 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"father\">{{cite news|accessdate=14 December 2012 |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/minister-poroshenko-and-his-father-registered-as-self-nominees-for-districts-in-vinnytsia-region-311570.html |title=Minister Poroshenko and his father registered as self-nominees for Vinnytsia region |work=Kyiv Post |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=15 August 2012 |url-status=live |archivedate=20 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220053732/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/minister-poroshenko-and-his-father-registered-as-self-nominees-for-districts-in-vinnytsia-region-311570.html |df=dmy }}</ref> He did not enter any faction in parliament<ref name=\"indipor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/poroshenko-not-intending-to-join-any-faction-317539.html |title=Poroshenko not intending to join any faction |work=[[Kyiv Post]] |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=14 December 2012 |url-status=live |archivedate=14 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214133925/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/poroshenko-not-intending-to-join-any-faction-317539.html |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|date=20 June 2013 |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/poroshenko-fears-uncontrolled-economic-situation-in-ukraine-due-to-foreign-borrowing-325913.html |title=Poroshenko fears uncontrolled economic situation in Ukraine due to foreign borrowing |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |work=Kyiv Post |accessdate=20 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923233703/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/poroshenko-fears-uncontrolled-economic-situation-in-ukraine-due-to-foreign-borrowing-325913.html |archivedate=23 September 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> and became member of the [[Committee of the Verkhovna Rada on issues of European integration|committee on European Integration]].<ref name=PpofileSO/> Poroshenko's father Oleksiy did intend to take part in the elections too in single-member district number 16 (also located in Vinnytsia Oblast), but withdrew his candidacy for health reasons.<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.rbc.ua/rus/vyboru2012/person/o105 Candidates single-mandate constituency \u2116 16], [[RBC Ukraine]]</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/697310-poroshenkos-father-changes-his-mind-to-withdraw-his-candidacy-from-elections.html |title=Poroshenko's father changes his mind to withdraw his candidacy from elections |agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]] |date=25 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904162445/http://www.unian.info/politics/697310-poroshenkos-father-changes-his-mind-to-withdraw-his-candidacy-from-elections.html |archivedate=4 September 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In mid-February 2013, Poroshenko hinted he would run for [[Mayor of Kiev]] in the [[2013 Kiev mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ukrainebusiness.com.ua/news/8734.html |title=Poroshenko appears set to join race for Kyiv mayor |publisher=Ukraine Business Online |date=12 February 2013 |accessdate=15 February 2013 |archivedate=19 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419005026/http://www.ukrainebusiness.com.ua/news/8734.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the registration certificate of Solidarity was cancelled because for more than 10 years had not participated in any election.<ref name=PoroWP/> Poroshenko then launched and became leader of the [[National Alliance of freedom and Ukrainian patriotism \"OFFENSIVE\"]] (NASTUP), which was renamed \"All-Ukrainian Union Solidarity\" (BOS).<ref name=PoroWP/>\n\n===2014 Ukrainian revolution===\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Poses for a Photo With Ukranian Opposition Leaders in Munich.jpg|thumb|Ukrainian opposition leaders [[Vitali Klitschko]], Poroshenko (second left) and [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]] (right) with [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] (second right) at the [[Munich Security Conference]], 2014.]]\n{{main|2014 Ukrainian revolution}}\n\nPoroshenko actively and financially supported the [[Euromaidan]] protests between November 2013 and February 2014,<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> leading to an upsurge in his popularity, although <ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> he did not participate in negotiations between then President Yanukovych and the Euromaidan parliamentary opposition parties [[Batkivshchyna]], [[Svoboda (party)|Svoboda]] and [[UDAR]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[Lally Weymouth]], Poroshenko said: \"From the beginning, I was one of the organizers of the Maidan. My television channel \u2014 Channel 5 \u2014 played a tremendously important role. ... At that time, Channel 5 started to broadcast, there were just 2,000 people on the Maidan. But during the night, people went by foot \u2014 seven, eight, nine, 10 kilometers \u2014 understanding this is a fight for Ukrainian freedom and democracy. In four hours, almost 30,000 people were there.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/interview-with-ukrainian-presidential-candidate-petro-poroshenko/2014/04/25/74c73a48-cbbd-11e3-93eb-6c0037dde2ad_story.html|title=Interview with Ukrainian presidential candidate Petro Poroshenko|date=25 April 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604095721/http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/interview-with-ukrainian-presidential-candidate-petro-poroshenko/2014/04/25/74c73a48-cbbd-11e3-93eb-6c0037dde2ad_story.html|archivedate=4 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[BBC]] reported, \"Mr Poroshenko owns 5 Kanal TV, the most popular news channel in Ukraine, which showed clear pro-opposition sympathies during the months of political crisis in Kiev.\"<ref name=\"BBC Profile Poroshenko\"/>\n\nPoroshenko refused to join the [[First Yatsenyuk Government|Yatsenyuk Government]] (although he introduced his colleague [[Volodymyr Groysman]], the mayor of [[Vinnytsia]], into it), nor did he join any of the two newly created parliamentary factions [[Economic Development (parliamentary faction)|Economic Development]] and [[Sovereign European Ukraine]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/>\n\nOn 24 April 2014, Poroshenko visited [[Luhansk]], at the time [[Luhansk People's Republic#Occupation of government buildings|not controlled by Ukrainian authorities]].<ref name=KPp71016/> Just like previously in Crimea he was met by a blockade of hundreds of [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian locals]] at [[Luhansk Airport]].<ref name=KPp71016/> Poroshenko later claimed: \"When I traveled to [[Luhansk Oblast]], my car was fired at and there was an attempt to take our entire group hostage.\"<ref name=KPp71016/>\n\n===2014 presidential campaign===\n[[File:Poroshenko-2014-en.png|thumb|2014 presidential election percentage of vote for Poroshenko.]]\n{{main|2014 Ukrainian presidential election}}\n\nFollowing the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]] and the resulting removal of [[Viktor Yanukovych]] from the office of President of Ukraine, new presidential elections were scheduled to take place on 25 May 2014.<ref name=\"Yanuousted\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26312008 |title=Ukraine: Speaker Oleksandr Turchynov named interim president |work=BBC News |date=23 February 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327024822/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26312008 |archivedate=27 March 2014 |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|date=23 February 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |title=Ukraine protests timeline |work=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |archivedate=19 February 2014 |url-status=live |accessdate=29 March 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> In pre-election polls from March 2014, Poroshenko garnered the most support of all the prospective candidates, with one poll conducted by SOCIS giving him a rating of over 40%.<ref>[http://www.socis.kiev.ua/ \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f | \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0442\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0436\u0435\u043d\u044c SOCIS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070707/http://socis.kiev.ua/ |date=21 May 2014 }}. Socis.kiev.ua. Retrieved 28 May 2014.</ref> On 29 March he stated that he would run for president; at the same time [[Vitali Klitschko]] left the presidential contest, choosing to support Poroshenko's bid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198350.html |title=Klitschko will run for mayor of Kyiv |accessdate=29 March 2014 |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=29 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330005126/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198350.html |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=29 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198348.html |title=Klitschko believes only presidential candidate from democratic forces should be Poroshenko |url-status=live |archivedate=11 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011034026/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198348.html |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=29 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014 |author=Colin Freeman |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10731848/Petro-Poroshenko-the-billionaire-chocolate-baron-hoping-to-become-Ukraines-next-president.html |title=Petro Poroshenko, the billionaire chocolate baron hoping to become Ukraine's next president |work=The Daily Telegraph |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330003104/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10731848/Petro-Poroshenko-the-billionaire-chocolate-baron-hoping-to-become-Ukraines-next-president.html |url-status=live |archivedate=30 March 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/03/29/ukraine-former-boxer-vitaliy-klitschko-ends-presidential-bid-and-backs-/ |title=Ukraine: former boxer Vitaliy Klitschko ends presidential bid and backs Poroshenko |publisher=[[Euronews]] |date=29 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330021851/http://www.euronews.com/2014/03/29/ukraine-former-boxer-vitaliy-klitschko-ends-presidential-bid-and-backs-/ |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Poroshenko stated, \"If I am elected, I will be honest and sell the Roshen Concern.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/198849.html |title=Poroshenko ready to sell Roshen if elected president |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=2 April 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080918/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/198849.html |archivedate=7 April 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> He also said in early April that the level of popular support for the idea of [[Ukraine\u2013NATO relations|Ukraine's joining NATO]] was too small to put on the agenda \"so as not to ruin the country.\"<ref>{{cite news|agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=2 April 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198839.html |title=Question of Ukraine's membership of NATO may split country \u2013 Poroshenko |archivedate=7 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080915/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198839.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> He also vowed not to sell his [[5 Kanal (Ukraine)|5 Kanal]] television channel.<ref name=\"HP\">{{cite news|date=25 May 2014|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304811904579583413180447156|title=Poroshenko Declares Victory in Ukraine Presidential Election|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=29 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528033721/http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304811904579583413180447156|archivedate=28 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 14 April, Poroshenko publicly endorsed the campaign of [[Jaros\u0142aw Gowin]]'s party [[Poland Together]] of neighboring Poland in this year's elections to the European Parliament, thanking Gowin's party colleague [[Pawe\u0142 Kowal]] for supporting Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url=http://www.polskieradio.pl/5/3/Artykul/1098445,Polska-Razem-czarnym-koniem-Mocne-slowa-Gowina |title=Polska Razem czarnym koniem? Mocne s\u0142owa Gowina |trans-title=Polish Total black horse? Strong words Gowin |date=12 April 2014 |language=pl |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415025816/http://www.polskieradio.pl/5/3/Artykul/1098445%2CPolska-Razem-czarnym-koniem-Mocne-slowa-Gowina |archivedate=15 April 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPoroshenko's election slogan was: \"Live in a new way \u2013 Poroshenko!\".<ref name=\"PpofileSO\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/profile-of-petro-poroshenko-in-the-run-up-to-the-ukraine-elections-a-970325.html |title=Ukraine Election: The Chocolate King Rises |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |date=22 May 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=28 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528051631/http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/profile-of-petro-poroshenko-in-the-run-up-to-the-ukraine-elections-a-970325.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May, the [[Central Election Commission of Ukraine]] announced that Poroshenko had won 25 May presidential election, with 54.7% of the votes.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=29 May 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/207146.html |title=Poroshenko wins presidential election with 54.7% of vote \u2013 CEC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529201857/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/207146.html |archivedate=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"wp\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukraine-talks-set-to-open-without-pro-russian-separatists/2014/05/14/621dbc6a-c7d9-40bc-b2e5-814a4108bbef_story.html|title=Ukraine talks set to open without pro-Russian separatists|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=29 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528213228/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukraine-talks-set-to-open-without-pro-russian-separatists/2014/05/14/621dbc6a-c7d9-40bc-b2e5-814a4108bbef_story.html|archivedate=28 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Runners and risks\">{{cite news|date=22 May 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27518989 |title=Ukraine elections: Runners and risks |work=BBC News |accessdate=29 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527092109/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27518989 |archivedate=27 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"BBCESR\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8460978.stm |title=Q&A: Ukraine presidential election |work=BBC News |date=7 February 2010 |accessdate=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=29 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429045939/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8460978.stm |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"CEC election results\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Radio Ukraine International]] |accessdate=29 May 2014 |url=http://nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/566632/ |title=Poroshenko wins presidential election with 54.7% of vote \u2013 CEC |date=29 May 2014 |archivedate=29 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529212731/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/566632/ |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|publisher=\u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444 |url=http://telegraf.com.ua/ukraina/politika/1300294-rezultatyi-vyiborov-prezidenta-ukrainyi-2014-tsik-obrabotala-51-99.html |script-title=ru:\u0412\u043d\u0435\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b |trans-title=Results election of Ukrainian president |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2014 |language=ru |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529233925/http://telegraf.com.ua/ukraina/politika/1300294-rezultatyi-vyiborov-prezidenta-ukrainyi-2014-tsik-obrabotala-51-99.html |archivedate=29 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"New Ukrainian president 5-year term\">{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/205114.html |title=New Ukrainian president will be elected for 5-year term \u2013 Constitutional Court |date=16 May 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2014 |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517121006/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/205114.html |archivedate=17 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit in [[Berlin]], Poroshenko stated that Russian separatists in the Donbass \"don't represent anybody. We have to restore law and order and sweep the terrorists off the street.\"<ref name=\"separatists\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/poroshenko-no-negotiations-with-separatists/a-17619764 |title=Poroshenko: 'No negotiations with separatists' |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=8 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524124039/http://www.dw.de/poroshenko-no-negotiations-with-separatists/a-17619764 |archivedate=24 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> He described as \"fake\" the planned 11 May [[2014 Donbass status referendums|Donbass status referendums]].<ref name=separatists/>\n\n==Presidency==\nWhen it became clear he had won the election on election day evening (on 25 May 2014) Poroshenko announced \"My first presidential trip will be to [[Donbas]]\", where [[2014 pro-Russian conflict in Ukraine|armed pro-Russian rebels]] had declared the separatist republics [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and [[Luhansk People's Republic]] and control a large part of the region.<ref name=\"HP\"/><ref name=\"Ukraine crisis timeline BBC\">{{cite news|title=Ukraine crisis timeline |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |work=BBC News |accessdate=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530112656/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |archivedate=30 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko also vowed to continue the military operations by the Ukrainian government forces to end the armed insurgency claiming: \"The anti-terrorist operation cannot and should not last two or three months. It should and will last hours.\"<ref name=\"G26514P\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/26/poroshenko-peace-donetsk-airport-air-strike-separatists |title=Poroshenko promises calm 'in hours' amid battle to control Donetsk airport |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 May 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529072943/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/26/poroshenko-peace-donetsk-airport-air-strike-separatists |archivedate=29 May 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> He compared the armed pro-Russian rebels to [[Somali pirates]].<ref name=G26514P/> Poroshenko also called for negotiations with Russia in the presence of international intermediaries.<ref name=G26514P/> Russia responded by saying it did not need an intermediary in its bilateral relations with Ukraine.<ref name=G26514P/> As president-elect, Poroshenko promised to return Crimea,<ref name=G26514P/> which [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|was annexed by Russia]] in March 2014.<ref name=\"Ukraine crisis timeline BBC\"/><ref name=\"EU & Ukraine 17 April 2014 FACT SHEET\">{{cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/statements/docs/2014/140417_03_en.pdf |title=EU & Ukraine 17 April 2014 FACT SHEET |publisher=[[European External Action Service]] |format=PDF |date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514174415/http://eeas.europa.eu/statements/docs/2014/140417_03_en.pdf |archivedate=14 May 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>{{efn|The status of the Crimea and of the city of [[Sevastopol]] is currently [[2014 Crimean crisis|under dispute between Russia and Ukraine]]; Ukraine and the majority of the international community consider the Crimea to be an [[autonomous republic]] of Ukraine and Sevastopol to be one of Ukraine's [[cities with special status]], while Russia, on the other hand, considers the Crimea to be a [[federal subject of Russia]] and Sevastopol to be one of Russia's three [[federal cities of Russia|federal cities]].<ref name=\"Ukraine crisis timeline BBC\"/><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=Gutterman |first1=Steve |last2=Polityuk |first2=Pavel |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/18/us-ukraine-crisis-idUSBREA1Q1E820140318 |title=Putin signs Crimea treaty, will not seize other Ukraine regions |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |archivedate=29 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329012404/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/18/us-ukraine-crisis-idUSBREA1Q1E820140318 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>}} He also vowed to hold new [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections in 2014]].<ref>{{cite news|date=25 May 2014|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukrainians-head-to-the-polls-to-elect-a-new-president-except-in-the-restive-east/2014/05/25/2680fad4-e9f7-4118-923e-852b01351b39_story.html|title=In Ukrainian election, chocolate tycoon Poroshenko claims victory|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904072819/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukrainians-head-to-the-polls-to-elect-a-new-president-except-in-the-restive-east/2014/05/25/2680fad4-e9f7-4118-923e-852b01351b39_story.html|archivedate=4 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Inauguration===\nPoroshenko was inaugurated in the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (parliament) on 7 June 2014.<ref name=\"Inaugurated 7 June 2014\">{{cite news|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20140529-707812.html|title=Petro Poroshenko to Be Inaugurated as Ukraine President June 7|author=Lukas Alpert|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=29 May 2014|accessdate=29 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529234158/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20140529-707812.html |archivedate=29 May 2014}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/207670.html|title=Rada decides to hold inauguration of Poroshenko on June 7 at 1000|agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]]|date=3 June 2014|accessdate=3 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140603165249/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/207670.html|archivedate=3 June 2014}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208367.html|title=Poroshenko sworn in as Ukrainian president|agency=Interfax-Ukraine|date=7 June 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=7 June 2014|archivedate=1 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701184604/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208367.html}}</ref> In his inaugural address he stressed that [[2014 Crimean crisis|Ukraine would not give up Crimea]] and stressed the unity of Ukraine.<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/> He promised an amnesty \"for those who do not have blood on their hands\" to the separatist and [[Russophilia|pro-Russia]] insurgents of the [[2014 pro-Russian conflict in Ukraine]] and to the [[Ukrainian nationalist]] groups that oppose them, but added: \"Talking to gangsters and killers is not our path\".<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/> He also called for early regional elections in [[Eastern Ukraine]].<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/> Poroshenko also stated that he would sign the economic part of the [[Ukraine\u2013European Union Association Agreement]] and that this was the first step towards full [[Ukrainian EU Membership]].<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/> During the speech he stated he saw \"[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] as the only state language\" but also spoke of the \"guarantees [of] the unhindered development of Russian and all [[Languages of Ukraine|the other languages]]\".<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/> Part of the speech was in Russian.<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\">{{cite news |publisher=[[theguardian.com]] |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=7 June 2014 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/07/ukraine-president-poroshenko-crimea-putin |title=Ukraine president vows not to give up Crimea |url-status=live |archivedate=13 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613194756/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/07/ukraine-president-poroshenko-crimea-putin |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27745278 |title=Ukraine's Poroshenko sworn in and sets out peace plan |work=BBC News |date=7 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609033038/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27745278 |archivedate=9 June 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27746994 |title=Excerpts from Poroshenko's speech |work=BBC News Online |date=7 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608013854/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27746994 |archivedate=8 June 2014 |url-status=live }}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/06/07/ukraine-s-poroshenko-outlines-peace-plan-at-inauguration/ |title=Ukraine's President Poroshenko pushes for peace at inauguration |publisher=[[Euronews]] |date=7 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609235153/http://euronews.com/2014/06/07/ukraine-s-poroshenko-outlines-peace-plan-at-inauguration |archivedate=9 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/06/07/poroshenko-offers-escape-for-rebels-but-no-compromise-over-weapons/ |title=Poroshenko offers escape for rebels but no compromise over weapons |publisher=Euronews |date=7 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701202739/http://www.euronews.com/2014/06/07/poroshenko-offers-escape-for-rebels-but-no-compromise-over-weapons/ |archivedate=1 July 2014 |url-status=live }}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2014/06/7/7028330/ |script-title=uk:\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0456\u0434 \u0447\u0430\u0441 \u0446\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u0456\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0457. \u041f\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0442 |trans-title=Speech by President of Ukraine during the inauguration ceremony. Full text |newspaper=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=7 June 2014 |language=uk |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607090456/http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2014/06/7/7028330/ |archivedate=7 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Petro Porochenko au Conseil de l\u2019Europe Strasbourg 26 juin 2014 03.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko delivers a speech to the [[Council of Europe]] parliamentary assembly in [[Strasbourg]], 26 June 2014.]]\n\nThe inauguration was attended by about 50 foreign delegations, including US Vice President [[Joe Biden]], [[President of Poland]] [[Bronis\u0142aw Komorowski]], [[President of Belarus]] [[Alexander Lukashenko]], [[President of Lithuania]] [[Dalia Grybauskait\u0117]], [[President of Switzerland]] and the [[OSCE]] Chairman-in-Office [[Didier Burkhalter]], [[President of Germany]] [[Joachim Gauck]], [[President of Georgia]] [[Giorgi Margvelashvili]], [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Stephen Harper]], [[Prime Minister of Hungary]] [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]], [[President of the European Council]] [[Herman Van Rompuy]], the OSCE Secretary General [[Lamberto Zannier]], [[United Nations Department of Political Affairs|UN Under-Secretary-General for Political Affairs]] [[Jeffrey D. Feltman|Jeffrey Feldman]], [[Ministry of Culture of the People's Republic of China|China's Minister of Culture]] [[Cai Wu]] and [[Ambassador of Russia to Ukraine]] [[Mikhail Zurabov]]<ref name=\"Guest Poro inaug\">{{cite news|newspaper=Ukrayinska Pravda|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028262/|script-title=uk:\u041d\u0430 \u0456\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044e \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0437 56 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d|trans-title=At the inauguration Poroshenko come delegations from 56 countries|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=7 June 2014|language=uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609232456/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028262/|archivedate=9 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/06/07/ukraine-international-recognition-for-president-poroshenko/ |title=Ukraine: International recognition for President Poroshenko |publisher=[[Euronews]] |date=7 June 2014 |accessdate=7 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708222139/http://www.euronews.com/2014/06/07/ukraine-international-recognition-for-president-poroshenko/ |archivedate=8 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Former [[Prime Minister of Ukraine]] [[Yulia Tymoshenko]] was also present.<ref name=\"Poro sworn in speech\"/><ref name=\"Guest Poro inaug\"/> After the inauguration ceremony Tymoshenko said about Poroshenko \"I think Ukraine has found a very powerful additional factor of stability\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028359|script-title=uk:\u0422\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u2013 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0431\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456|trans-title=Tymoshenko: President Poroshenko \u2013 a powerful factor of stability|newspaper=Ukrayinska Pravda|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=7 June 2014|language=uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609232601/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028359/|archivedate=9 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic policy===\n\n====Peace plan for Eastern Ukraine====\n{{main|2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine}}\nAt the time of his inauguration, [[2014 pro-Russian conflict in Ukraine|armed pro-Russian rebels]], after [[2014 Donbass status referendums|disputed referendums]], had declared the independence of the separatist [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and [[Luhansk People's Republic]] and controlled a large part of [[Donbass]], but were largely considered to be illegitimate by the international community.<ref name=\"HP\"/><ref name=\"Ukraine crisis timeline BBC\"/> After the inauguration, Poroshenko launched a \"peace\" plan envisioned to garner the recognition of the [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential elections in Ukraine]] by Russia, consisting of a cease-fire with the separatists (named \"terrorists\" by Poroshenko himself) and the establishment of a humanitarian corridor for civilians (\"who are not involved in the conflict\").<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208898.html |title=Poroshenko doesn't rule out roundtable in Donetsk involving parties to conflict |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701044007/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208898.html |archivedate=1 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko warned that he had a \"Plan B\" if the initial peace plan was rejected.<ref name=\"Plan B\"/>\n\n====Decentralization of power====\n[[File:\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e.jpg|thumb|left|Poroshenko in Melitopol (2014)]]\nIn mid-June Poroshenko started the process of amending [[Ukraine's constitution]] to achieve Ukraine's [[Decentralisation in Ukraine|administrative decentralization]].<ref name=\"Poro dc Powers\"/> According to Poroshenko (on 16 June 2014) this was \"a key element of [[Petro Poroshenko#Peace plan for Eastern Ukraine|the peace plan]]\".<ref name=\"Poro dc Powers\">{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/209550.html |title=Amendments to Ukraine's Constitution to be tabled in parliament this week \u2013 Poroshenko |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=16 June 2014 |archivedate=1 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701043708/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/209550.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In his draft constitutional amendments of June 2014 proposed changing the [[administrative divisions of Ukraine]], which should include regions (replacing the current [[Oblasts of Ukraine|oblasts]]), districts and \"[[Administrative divisions of Ukraine#United territorial communities|hromadas]]\" (united territorial communities).<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211043.html |title=Poroshenko suggests granting status of regions to Crimea, Kyiv, Sevastopol, creating new political subdivision of 'community' |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701043549/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211043.html |archivedate=1 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In these amendments he also proposed that \"Village, city, district and regional administrations will be able to determine the status of the [[Russian language]] and other [[Languages of Ukraine|national minority languages of Ukraine]] in accordance with the procedure established by the law and within the borders of their administrative and territorial units\".<ref name=\"Poro UK SL, R RL\">{{cite news|date=26 June 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211041.html |title=Authorities in Ukrainian regions may be allowed to determine status of national minority languages |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |accessdate=26 June 2014 |archivedate=1 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701043340/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211041.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> He proposed that [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] remained the only state language of Ukraine.<ref name=\"Poro UK SL, R RL\"/> Poroshenko further proposed to create the post of presidential representatives who would supervise the enforcement of the Ukrainian constitution and laws and the observation of human rights and freedoms in [[Oblasts of Ukraine|oblasts]] and [[Raions of Ukraine|raions]]/[[Raions of cities in Ukraine|raions of cities]].<ref name=\"Ukrainian president proposes representatives to regions\"/> In case of an \"emergency situation or martial law regime\" they will \"guide and organize\" in the territories they are stationed in.<ref name=\"Ukrainian president proposes representatives to regions\">{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211030.html |title=Ukrainian president proposes to appoint representatives to regions |agency=Interfax-Ukraine |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701040905/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211030.html |archivedate=1 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Batkivshchyna]], a key coalition partner in the [[First Yatsenyuk Government|Yatsenyuk Government]], came out against the plan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-defence-idUSKBN0F80CF20140703 |title=Ukraine's Poroshenko names new defence chiefs in shake-up |agency=Reuters |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703140826/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/03/us-ukraine-crisis-defence-idUSKBN0F80CF20140703 |archivedate=3 July 2014 |url-status=live |date=3 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> {{why?|date=June 2018}}\n\nHe repeatedly spoken out against [[federalization]].<ref name=\"PPnofed\">\"[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/250254.html Documents signed in Minsk don't envision federalization, autonomy for Donbas \u2013 Poroshenko] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224215420/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/250254.html|date=24 February 2015}}\". [[Interfax-Ukraine]]. 12 February 2015.</ref><ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/273848.html Poroshenko rules out federalization of Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624014948/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/273848.html |date=24 June 2015 }}. [[Interfax-Ukraine]]. 23 June 2015.<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/274559.html Ukraine to remain unitary state after constitution is amended \u2013 Poroshenko] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627014147/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/274559.html |date=27 June 2015 }}. [[Interfax-Ukraine]]. 26 June 2015.</ref> and did not seek to increase [[President of Ukraine#Duties and powers|his presidential powers]].<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/275000.html Semi-presidential form of government is optimal for Ukraine \u2013 Poroshenko] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802010136/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/275000.html |date=2 August 2015 }}. [[Interfax-Ukraine]]. 30 June 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Putin Renzi Poroshenko.jpeg|thumb|Poroshenko, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Italian Prime Minister [[Matteo Renzi]], 18 October 2015]]\n1 July 2015 decentralization draft law gave local authorities the right to oversee how their tax revenues are spent.<ref name=\"pddl1715\">[http://www.rferl.mobi/a/ukraine-constitution-changes-poroshenko-/27104769.html Poroshenko Unveils Constitutional Changes], [[Radio Free Europe]] (1 July 2015)</ref> The draft law did not give an [[Autonomous administrative division|autonomous status]] to [[Donbass]], as demanded by the pro-Russian rebels there, but gave the region partial self-rule for three years.<ref name=pddl1715/>\n\n====Dissolution of Parliament====\n{{Main|2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election}}\nOn 25 August 2014, Poroshenko called a [[snap election]] to the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (Ukraine's parliament), [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|to be held 26 October 2014]].<ref name=\"PsUE25814\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-08-25/ukraine-president-poroshenko-calls-snap-general-election.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825232937/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-08-25/ukraine-president-poroshenko-calls-snap-general-election.html|archivedate=25 August 2014|title=Ukraine President Poroshenko Calls Snap General Election|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCtsP25814\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28931054 |title=Ukraine crisis: President calls snap vote amid fighting |work=BBC News |date=25 August 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2014 |archivedate=27 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827104753/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28931054 |df=dmy }}</ref> According to him this was necessary \"to purify the Rada of the mainstay of [former president] [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\". These deputies, Poroshenko said, \"clearly do not represent the people who elected them\".<ref name=SPne25814/> Poroshenko also said that these Rada deputies were responsible for \"the [[Dictatorship laws in Ukraine|[January 2014] Dictatorship laws]] that took the lives of the [[Heavenly hundred]]\".<ref name=SPne25814/> Poroshenko also stated that many of the (then) current MPs were \"direct sponsors and accomplices or at least sympathizers of militant-separatists\".<ref name=\"SPne25814\">[http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2014/08/25/Ukrainian-President-dissolves-Parliament-announces-early-elections/3261408995210/ Ukrainian President dissolves Parliament, announces early elections] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831062559/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2014/08/25/Ukrainian-President-dissolves-Parliament-announces-early-elections/3261408995210/ |date=31 August 2014 }}, [[United Press International]] (25 August 2014)<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/ukraine-s-petro-poroshenko-announces-new-parliamentary-elections/505837.html |title=Ukraine's Petro Poroshenko Dissolves Parliament, Sets Election Date |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=26 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827121528/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/ukraine-s-petro-poroshenko-announces-new-parliamentary-elections/505837.html |archivedate=27 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}<br />[https://web.archive.org/web/20140829180501/http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/31081.html President's address on the occasion of early parliamentary elections of 26 October], [[Presidential Administration of Ukraine]] (25 August 2014)</ref>\n\nPoroshenko had pressed for the elections since his victory in the [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|May 2014 presidential election]].<ref name=\"IUEEUZZ\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 August 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211079.html |title=Poroshenko hopes early parliamentary elections in Ukraine will take place in October |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=26 June 2014 |archivedate=27 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027041537/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211079.html |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"IUEEU\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 August 2014 |date=19 June 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210172.html |title=Poroshenko hopes for early parliamentary elections in Ukraine this fall \u2013 presidential envoy |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |archivedate=18 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018230314/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210172.html |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"WPEEU\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukrainians-head-to-the-polls-to-elect-a-new-president-except-in-the-restive-east/2014/05/25/2680fad4-e9f7-4118-923e-852b01351b39_story.html|title=In Ukrainian election, chocolate tycoon Poroshenko claims victory|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904072819/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ukrainians-head-to-the-polls-to-elect-a-new-president-except-in-the-restive-east/2014/05/25/2680fad4-e9f7-4118-923e-852b01351b39_story.html|archivedate=4 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2014, the party congress of [[National Alliance of Freedom and Ukrainian patriotism \"OFFENSIVE\"|All-Ukrainian Party of Peace and Unity]] adopted a new name: \"[[Petro Poroshenko Bloc \"Solidarity\"|Petro Poroshenko Bloc]]\" (BPP).<ref name=\"renamed Bloc of Petro Poroshenko\">{{cite news|date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2014 |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/220240.html |title=Poroshenko wants coalition to be formed before parliamentary elections |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |archivedate=3 July 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703140826/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/220240.html |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/220216.html |title=Solidarity Party to be renamed Bloc of Petro Poroshenko \u2013 congress |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=27 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831002633/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/220216.html |archivedate=31 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"PoroWP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/rus/articles/2014/06/6/7028205/view_print/|script-title=uk:\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0432\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0443|trans-title=Poroshenko goes to work|work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|date=6 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230000/http://www.pravda.com.ua/rus/articles/2014/06/6/7028205/view_print/|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all|language=uk}}</ref><ref name=\"PoroPMyth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2014/05/16/7025568|script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0456 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0435\u0447\u0430|date=16 May 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014|language=uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830053322/http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2014/05/16/7025568/|archivedate=30 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015, the Petro Poroshenko Bloc was renamed in \"[[Petro Poroshenko Bloc \"Solidarity\"]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-politics/1823650-bloc_of_petro_poroshenko_to_change_name_329651.html|title=Bloc of Petro Poroshenko to change name|work=Ukrinform.net|date=10 March 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111153024/http://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-politics/1823650-bloc_of_petro_poroshenko_to_change_name_329651.html|archive-date=11 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Nuclear weapons====\nOn 13 December 2014, Poroshenko stated that he did not want [[Nuclear weapons and Ukraine|Ukraine to become a nuclear power again]].<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/239730.html Ukraine has no ambitions to become nuclear power again \u2013 Poroshenko] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214005906/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/239730.html |date=14 December 2014 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (13 December 2014)</ref>\n\n====Decommunization and deoligarchization====\n[[File:\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043f\u0456\u0434 \u0447\u0430\u0441 \u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0443 \u0443 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0456 (2016 \u0440\u0456\u043a).jpg|thumb|Petro Poroshenko in Poltava (2016)]]\nOn 15 May 2015, Poroshenko signed a bill into law that started a six months period for [[Decommunization in Ukraine|the removal of communist monuments and the mandatory renaming of streets and other public places and settlements with a name related to]] Communism.<ref name=\"decommupbbcU\">[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/05/15/7068057/ Poroshenko signed the laws about decommunization] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423181130/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/05/15/7068057/ |date=23 April 2016 }}. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 15 May 2015<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/265988.html Poroshenko signs laws on denouncing Communist, Nazi regimes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819162411/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/265988.html |date=19 August 2016 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]]. 15 May 20<br />[http://www.unian.info/politics/1078854-poroshenko-time-for-ukraine-to-resolutely-get-rid-of-communist-symbols.html Poroshenko: Time for Ukraine to resolutely get rid of Communist symbols] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518092853/http://www.unian.info/politics/1078854-poroshenko-time-for-ukraine-to-resolutely-get-rid-of-communist-symbols.html |date=18 May 2015 }}, [[UNIAN]]. 17 May 2015<br />[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32267075 Goodbye, Lenin: Ukraine moves to ban communist symbols] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307200441/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32267075 |date=7 March 2016 }}, [[BBC News]] (14 April 2015)</ref> According to Poroshenko \"I did what I had to\"; adding\n\"Ukraine as a state has done its job, then historians should work, while the government should take care of the future\".<ref name=decommupbbcU/> Poroshenko believes that the [[Political repression in the Soviet Union|communist repression]] and [[holodomor]] of the [[Soviet Union]] are on par with the [[Nazi atrocities|Nazi crimes]] of the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/politics/2015/05/150517_poroshenko_red_terror_she|script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u0447\u0430\u0441 \u043e\u0447\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0432|trans-title=Poroshenko: time to clear Ukraine of communist symbols|language=uk|work=[[BBC Ukrainian]]|date=17 May 2015|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113164921/http://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/politics/2015/05/150517_poroshenko_red_terror_she|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The legislation (Poroshenko signed on 15 May 2015) also provides \"public recognition to anyone who fought for [[Ukrainian independence]] in the 20th century\",<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/20/ukraine-decommunisation-law-soviet Ukraine to rewrite Soviet history with controversial 'decommunisation' laws] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723085903/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/20/ukraine-decommunisation-law-soviet |date=23 July 2016 }}\". ''[[The Guardian]]''. 20 April 2015.</ref> including the controversial [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]] (UPA) combatants led by [[Roman Shukhevych]] and [[Stepan Bandera]].<ref name=decommupbbcU/>\n\nPoroshenko said in an interview with Germany's ''Bild'' newspaper that \"If I am elected, I'll wipe the slate clean and will sell the [[Roshen]] concern. As president of Ukraine, I will and want to only focus on the well-being of the nation.\"<ref>\"[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-04-02/poroshenko-to-sell-roshen-if-elected-ukrainian-president-bild Poroshenko to Sell Roshen If Elected Ukrainian President: Bild] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322075302/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-04-02/poroshenko-to-sell-roshen-if-elected-ukrainian-president-bild |date=22 March 2017 }}\". [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]. 2 April 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2015, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko accepted the resignation of billionaire [[Ihor Kolomoyskyi|Ihor Kolomoisky]] as governor of [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast|Dnipro region]] over the control of oil companies.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Powerful Ukrainian Governor Kolomoyskiy Resigns|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-kolomoisky-/26919383.html|newspaper=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|date=25 March 2015|access-date=9 June 2015}}</ref> \"There will be no more oligarchs in Ukraine,\" Poroshenko said adding that \"oligarchs must pay more [taxes] than the middle class and more than small business.\" The president underscored that \"the program of de-oligarchization will be put into life\". Poroshenko promised that he will fight against the [[Ukrainian oligarchs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.5.ua/polityka/V-Ukraini-bilshe-ne-bude-oliharkhiv--Poroshenko-82237.html|title=IN UKRAINE THERE WILL BE NO MORE OLIGARCHS \u2013 POROSHENKO|publisher=5.ua|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=2015-05-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601235924/http://www.5.ua/polityka/V-Ukraini-bilshe-ne-bude-oliharkhiv--Poroshenko-82237.html|archivedate=1 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, President Poroshenko confirmed the status of veterans and combatants for independence of Ukraine for the armed units of the [[Organization of Ukrainian Nationalists]] (OUN) and the [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]] (UPA).<ref>{{cite news |title=Poroshenko enacts law granting fighters for Ukraine's independence in 20th century combatant status |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10388085-poroshenko-enacts-law-granting-fighters-for-ukraine-s-independence-in-20th-century-combatant-status.html |work=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]] |date=23 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Language policy====\n{{See also|Language policy in Ukraine}}\n\nIn 2016, a New rule came into force requiring Ukraine's radio stations to play a quota of Ukrainian-language songs each day. The law also requires TV and radio broadcasters to ensure 60% of programs such as news and analysis are in Ukrainian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-news-from-elsewhere-37908828|title=Language quotas for Ukraine radio shows|date=8 November 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2017, a new law on education was signed by President Poroshenko (draft approved by Rada on September 5, 2017) which says that the [[Ukrainian language]] is the language of education at all levels except for one or more subjects that are allowed to be taught in two or more languages, namely [[English language|English]] or one of the other [[official languages of the European Union]]. The law stipulates a 3-year transitional period to come in full effect.<ref name=\"UNIAN 2159231\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/society/2159231-new-education-law-becomes-effective-in-ukraine.html|title=New education law becomes effective in Ukraine|website=unian.info}}</ref><ref name=\"law\">[http://zakon2.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/2145-19/page \u041f\u0440\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0443] | \u0432\u0456\u0434 05.09.2017 \u2116 2145-VIII (\u0421\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u043d\u043a\u0430 1 \u0437 7)</ref> In February 2018 this period was extended until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/2395156-ukraine-agrees-to-concessions-to-hungary-in-language-row.html|title=Ukraine agrees to concessions to Hungary in language row|website=unian.info}}</ref> The law was condemned by [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe|PACE]] that called it \"a major impediment to the teaching of national minorities\".<ref name=\"PACE\">{{Cite web|url=http://assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/XRef/Xref-XML2HTML-EN.asp?fileid=24218&lang=en|title=PACE \u2013 Resolution 2189 (2017) \u2013 The new Ukrainian law on education: a major impediment to the teaching of national minorities' mother tongues|website=assembly.coe.int}}</ref> The law also faced criticism from officials in [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] and [[Russia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-language-legislation-minority-languages-russia-hungary-romania/28753925.html|title=Ukrainian Language Bill Facing Barrage Of Criticism From Minorities, Foreign Capitals|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty}}</ref> ([[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] and [[Romanian language|Romanian]] are official languages of the European Union, [[Russian language|Russian]] is not.<ref>{{cite web|title=Consolidated version of Regulation No 1 determining the languages to be used by the European Economic Community|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CONSLEG:1958R0001:20070101:EN:PDF|format=PDF|work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]]|publisher=[[European Union]]|accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Official EU languages\">{{cite web|title=Languages of Europe \u2013 Official EU languages|url=http://ec.europa.eu/languages/policy/linguistic-diversity/official-languages-eu_en.htm|publisher=[[European Commission]]|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>) Ukrainian officials stressed that the new law complies fully with European norms on minority rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-41565090|title=Hungary in language dispute with Ukraine|date=10 October 2017|via=bbc.com}}</ref> [[File:\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u0456\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0443 \u043c\u043e\u0432\u0443; \u041c\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u2013 \u0446\u0435 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430, \u043d\u0430 \u044f\u043a\u0456\u0439 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0454\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f \u0456 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u0430 1.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko and [[Andriy Parubiy]] signing the law \"On provision of the functioning of the Ukrainian language as the State language\".]] The law does state that \"Persons belonging to [[indigenous peoples of Ukraine]] are guaranteed the right to study in public facilities of preschool and primary education in the language of instruction of the respective indigenous people, along with the state language of instruction\" in separate classes or groups.<ref name=\"law\" /> PACE describes this as a significant curtailing of the rights of indigenous peoples carried out without consultations with their representatives.<ref name=\"PACE\" /> On 27 June 2018 Ukrainian foreign minister [[Pavlo Klimkin]] stated that following the recommendation of the [[Venice Commission]] the language provision of the (September 2017) law on education will not apply to private schools and that every public school for national minorities \"will have broad powers to independently determine which classes will be taught in Ukrainian or their native language.\"<ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/10167494-hungary-realizes-ukraine-not-to-change-education-law-klimkin.html Hungary realizes Ukraine not to change education law \u2013 Klimkin], [[UNIAN]] (27 June 2018)</ref><ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/2342342-debate-on-language-provisions-of-ukraines-education-law-not-over-minister.html Debate on language provisions of Ukraine\u2019s education law not over \u2013 minister], [[UNIAN]] (12 January 2018)</ref>\n\nOn 15 May 2019, Poroshenko [[Language policy in Ukraine#Second vote and signature|signed the law \"On provision of the functioning of the Ukrainian language as the State language\"]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10550289-poroshenko-enacts-ukraine-s-language-law.html|title=Poroshenko enacts Ukraine's language law|date=15 May 2019|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/prezident-pidpisav-zakon-pro-derzhavnu-movu-mova-ce-platform-55319|title=President signed the law on the official language: Language is a platform on which the nation and state are built|date=15 May 2019|website=Official website of the President of Ukraine|language=en|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Hungarian Foreign Minister [[P\u00e9ter Szijj\u00e1rt\u00f3]] said the law was \"unacceptable\" and part of an \"anti-Hungarian policy\" of Poroshenko.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://112.international/politics/hungary-criticizes-ukrainian-language-law-39236.html|title=Hungary criticizes Ukrainian language law|date=26 April 2019|website=112.international|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref>|group=nb}}\n====Religious policy====\n\n[[File:Unification council of Orthodox Church in Ukraine 114.jpg|thumb|Inside the [[Saint Sophia's Cathedral, Kiev|Saint Sophia Cathedral]] during the unification council. In order from left to right: Poroshenko, [[Epiphanius I (Metropolitan of Kiev)|Epiphany]], {{Interlanguage link|Metropolitan Emmanuel of France|lt=|fr|Emmanuel Adamakis|WD=}}, [[Filaret (Denysenko)|Filaret]] (Filaret is wearing a [[skufia]]).]]\n{{See also|Unification council of the Orthodox churches of Ukraine|Orthodox Church of Ukraine}}{{See also|Autocephaly of the Orthodox Church of Ukraine|2018 Moscow\u2013Constantinople schism}}\nUnder Poroshenko the [[autocephalous]] [[Orthodox Church of Ukraine]] was created by the merging of the [[UOC-KP]] and the [[UAOC]], and two members of the [[UOC-MP]] in a [[Unification council of the Orthodox churches of Ukraine|unification council]] which also elected [[Epiphanius I (Metropolitan of Kiev)|Epiphanius I]] as its first [[Primate (bishop)|primate]]. The 11 October 2018 announce by [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarchate]] that it would \u2013 among other things \u2013 grant autocephaly to a Ukrainian church is one of the reasons which created  the [[2018 Moscow\u2013Constantinople schism|Moscow\u2013Constantinople schism]] when the Moscow Patriarchate severed full communion with the Ecumenical Patriarchate on 15 October 2018.\n\n====Corruption====\n[[Corruption in Ukraine]] is a widespread problem; although there are signs that during Poroshenko presidency it decreased (thanks to the [[Prozorro]] digital system).<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-47571043 'Corruption in Ukraine has to be stopped'], [[BBC news]] (20 March 2019)</ref> Poroshenko has signed a decree to create the [[Anti-Corruption Bureau|National Anti-Corruption Bureau of Ukraine]] to comply with the requirements of the [[International Monetary Fund]]. Since 2015, the Bureau has sent 189 cases to court, but no one significant was convicted. The head of the Special Anti-Corruption Prosecutor\u2019s Office reportedly coached suspects on how to avoid corruption charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lawfareblog.com/want-know-whats-next-russian-election-interference-pay-attention-ukraines-elections|title=Want to Know What\u2019s Next in Russian Election Interference? Pay Attention to Ukraine\u2019s Elections|date=28 March 2019|website=Lawfare}}</ref>\n\nA November 2018 [[EU Commission]] report praised some of Ukraine's reforms during Poroshenko's presidency, such as in healthcare, pensions and public administration.<ref name=\"47654242 Ukraine\"/> But judicial reforms were too slow, the report claimed, and \"there have been only few convictions in high-level corruption cases so far\".<ref name=\"47654242 Ukraine\"/> It also stated that too often attacks on civil society activists went unpunished.<ref name=\"47654242 Ukraine\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47654242 Ukraine election: Why comic Zelenskiy is real threat to Poroshenko], [[BBC news]] (27 March 2019)</ref>\n\nDuring Poroshenko's [[2019 Ukrainian presidential election|2019 campaign for reelection]] a major scandal broke out in which business partners of Poroshenko (but not Poroshenko himself) were accused of smuggling Russian components to Ukrainian defense factories at wildly inflated prices.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-02-27/ukraine-military-procurement-scandal-shakes-presidential-race This Graft Scandal May Be Too Much Even for Ukraine], [[Bloomberg News]] (February 27, 2019)</ref><ref name=\"47654242 Ukraine\"/>\n\nCritics of Poroshenko have pointed out that he removed jurisdiction of the National Anti-Corruption Bureau of Ukraine over records about off-the books payments to [[Paul J. Manafort]] who lobbied on behalf of former Ukraine president [[Viktor Yanukovych]] and served as campaign manager for [[Donald Trump]] during his presidential campaign.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/27/world/europe/mikhail-saakashvili-ukraine-citizenship-poroshenko.html Ukrainine's President sidelines opponent by stripping his citizenship] by Andrew Kramer, [[New York Times]]</ref> Moreover, Poroshenko stripped of Ukrainian citizenship [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] who criticized him for not fighting Ukrainian corruption.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/17/opinion/why-ukraine-is-losing-the-war-on-corruption.html Why Ukraine is losing the war on corruption] by [[Mikheil Saakashvili]]</ref>\n\nOn 11 April 2019, the [[High Anti-Corruption Court of Ukraine]] was established and Poroshenko signed the decree appointing the judges during an official ceremony.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-s-president-poroshenko-creates-anti-corruption-court/29875480.html|title=Ukraine's President Creates Anti-Corruption Court|date=11 April 2019|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n{{see also|List of international presidential trips made by Petro Poroshenko}}\n[[File:Barack Obama meets with Petro Poroshenko, June 5th 2014.jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] meets with Poroshenko, June 2014.]]\n\n====United States====\nOn 7 December 2015, Poroshenko had a meeting with U.S. Vice President [[Joe Biden]] in Kiev to discuss Ukrainian-American cooperation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nv.ua/ukr/ukraine/politics/zustrich-poroshenka-i-bajdena-osnovni-pidsumki-84433.html|title=Meeting Poroshenko and Biden: main results|publisher=nv.ua|date=8 December 2015|accessdate=2015-12-08|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209032739/http://nv.ua/ukr/ukraine/politics/zustrich-poroshenka-i-bajdena-osnovni-pidsumki-84433.html|archivedate=9 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He met [[Donald Trump]] in June 2017; the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] falsely accused him of paying Trump's lawyer [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] between 400,000 and 600,000 dollars to organize this meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110191349/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 January 2019|title=Ukraine 'paid Trump lawyer for talks'|first=Paul|last=Wood|date=23 May 2018|accessdate=26 November 2018|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Paul Wood |title=Trump lawyer 'paid by Ukraine' to arrange White House talks |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=23 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180524044242/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |archivedate=24 May 2018 |quote=Donald Trump's personal lawyer, Michael Cohen, received a secret payment of at least $400,000 (\u00a3300,000) to fix talks between the Ukrainian president and President Trump |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The BBC ended up having to state the allegation was untrue, apologizing to Poroshenko, deleting the article from its website, paying legal costs, and paying damages to Poroshenko.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC pays damages to Ukraine President Petro Poroshenko over report |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47719166 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=28 March 2019 |quote=\"We apologise to Mr Poroshenko for any distress caused and have agreed to pay him damages, legal costs and have participated in a joint statement in open court,\" the broadcaster said.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/bbc-ukraine-poroshenko-trump-michael-cohen-defamation-a8844061.html|title=BBC to pay 'substantial' damages to Ukrainian president over false allegations he authorised corrupt payment to meet Trump|date=2019-03-28|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06|quote=Jane Phillips, counsel for the BBC, said: \u201cThe BBC is happy to acknowledge that these claims about the claimant are completely untrue, and it is here, through me, to apologise to the claimant for any distress and embarrassment caused to him by the article and the broadcast.}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\nIn June 2014, Poroshenko forbade any [[Russia\u2013Ukraine relations|cooperation with Russia]] in the military sphere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/16/7029263/ |script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0432 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u044c-\u044f\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u0432\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0446\u044e \u0437 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0454\u044e \u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0439 \u0441\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0456 |trans-title=Poroshenko forbade any cooperation with Russia in the military sphere |newspaper=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=16 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617023142/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/16/7029263/ |archivedate=17 June 2014 |language=uk |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] on 26 June 2014 Poroshenko stated that [[Russia\u2013Ukraine relations|bilateral relations with Russia]] cannot be normalized unless Russia undoes its unilateral [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of]] [[Crimea]] and [[2014 Crimean crisis|returns its control of Crimea]] to Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211091.html |title=Ukraine cannot normalize relations with Russia without return of Crimea, says Poroshenko |agency=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 |archivedate=27 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627221848/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211091.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn [[Petro Poroshenko#Peace plan for Eastern Ukraine|Poroshenko's June 2014 Peace plan for Eastern Ukraine]], Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergei Lavrov]] commented \"it looks like an [[ultimatum]]\".<ref name=\"Plan B\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeerah.info/News/2014/June/22%20n/Poroshenko%20Warns%20of%20Detailed%20Plan%20B%20If%20Ukraine%20Ceasefire%20Fails,%20Gets%20Limited%20Support%20from%20Putin,%20June%2022,%202014.htm |title=Poroshenko warns of 'detailed Plan B' if Ukraine ceasefire fails |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=22 June 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=1 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701211805/http://www.aljazeerah.info/News/2014/June/22%20n/Poroshenko%20Warns%20of%20Detailed%20Plan%20B%20If%20Ukraine%20Ceasefire%20Fails%2C%20Gets%20Limited%20Support%20from%20Putin%2C%20June%2022%2C%202014.htm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2014, Poroshenko met with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] in [[Minsk]] where Putin called on Ukraine not to [[War in Donbass#Government push into Donetsk and Luhansk cities|escalate its offensive]]. Poroshenko responded by demanding Russia halt [[2014 Russian military intervention in Ukraine#Eastern Ukraine|its supplying of arms to separatist fighters]]. He said his country wanted a political compromise and promised the interests of Russian-speaking people in [[eastern Ukraine]] would be considered.<ref name=\"PutinPoroshenko\">{{cite news|title=Eastern Ukraine tensions figure in Putin and Poroshenko talks |url=http://www.moscownews.net/index.php/sid/225119533 |date=26 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014 |publisher=Moscow News |url-status=live |archivedate=3 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903063542/http://www.moscownews.net/index.php/sid/225119533 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n[[File:Petro Poroshenko in Slovenia in 2016 22.jpg|thumb|With the [[president of Slovenia]] [[Borut Pahor]] in [[Ljubljana]].]]\n\n====European Union====\n[[File:Poroschenko Merkel and Biden Security Conference February 2015.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko with [[Angela Merkel]] and [[Joe Biden]], 7 February 2015.]]\nThe [[European Union]] (EU) and Ukraine signed the economic part of the [[Ukraine\u2013European Union Association Agreement]] on 27 June 2014.<ref name=\"EU signs pacts with Ukraine, Georgia and Moldova\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28052645 |title=EU signs pacts with Ukraine, Georgia and Moldova |work=BBC News |date=27 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014 |archivedate=27 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627210422/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28052645 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Poroshenko stated that the day was \"Ukraine's most historic day since [[Declaration of Independence of Ukraine|independence in 1991]]\", describing it as a \"symbol of faith and unbreakable will\".<ref name=\"EU signs pacts with Ukraine, Georgia and Moldova\"/> He saw the signing as the start of preparations for [[Ukrainian EU Membership]].<ref name=\"EU signs pacts with Ukraine, Georgia and Moldova\"/>\n\n====NATO====\n[[File:Ukraine \u2013 NATO Commission chaired by Petro Poroshenko (2017-07-10) 38.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko with NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] in Kiev, 10 July 2017]]\nAt his speech at the opening session of [[8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|the new parliament]] on 27 November 2014, Poroshenko stated \"we've decided to return to the course of [[Ukraine-NATO relations|NATO integration]]\" because \"[[Foreign relations of Ukraine#Western relations|the nonalignment status of Ukraine proclaimed in 2010]] couldn't guarantee our security and territorial integrity\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/28/world/europe/a-tilt-toward-nato-in-ukraine-as-parliament-meets.html?action=click&contentCollection=Europe&module=RelatedCoverage&region=Marginalia&pgtype=article A Tilt Toward NATO in Ukraine as Parliament Meets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322074839/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/28/world/europe/a-tilt-toward-nato-in-ukraine-as-parliament-meets.html?action=click&contentCollection=Europe&module=RelatedCoverage&region=Marginalia&pgtype=article |date=22 March 2017 }}, [[The Wall Street Journal]] (27 November 2014)</ref> The Ukrainian parliament on 23 December 2014 voted 303 to 8 to repeal a 2010 bill that had made Ukraine a non-aligned state in a bill submitted by Poroshenko.<ref name=\"result of Russia PP\">{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241388.html|title=Ukraine has no alternative to Euro-Atlantic integration \u2013 Poroshenko|work=[[Interfax-Ukraine]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060210/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241388.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241359.html|title=Ukraine abolishes its non-aligned status \u2013 law|work=Interfax-Ukraine|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224003612/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241359.html|archivedate=24 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/12/23/ukraine-s-complicated-path-to-nato-membership/|title=Ukraine's complicated path to NATO membership|work=[[Euronews]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070543/http://www.euronews.com/2014/12/23/ukraine-s-complicated-path-to-nato-membership/|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/world/europe/ukraine-parliament-nato-vote.html?_r=2|title=Ukraine Takes Step Toward Joining NATO|work=[[New York Times]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322075205/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/world/europe/ukraine-parliament-nato-vote.html?_r=2|archivedate=22 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-ends-nonaligned-status-earning-quick-rebuke-from-russia-1419339226|title=Ukraine Ends 'Nonaligned' Status, Earning Quick Rebuke From Russia|work=[[The Wall Street journal]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222433/http://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-ends-nonaligned-status-earning-quick-rebuke-from-russia-1419339226|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 December 2014 Poroshenko vowed to hold a [[Ukrainian NATO membership referendum|referendum on joining NATO]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/12/30/new-year-new-hope-as-ukraine-paves-way-for-nato-membership/|title=New Year, new hope as Ukraine paves way for NATO membership|work=[[Euronews]]|date=30 December 2014|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075515/http://www.euronews.com/2014/12/30/new-year-new-hope-as-ukraine-paves-way-for-nato-membership/|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 22 September 2015 Poroshenko claimed that \"Russia's aggressive actions\" proved need for the [[enlargement of NATO]] and that the Ukrainian referendum on joining NATO would be held after \"every condition for the Ukrainian compliance with NATO membership criteria\" was met by \"reforming our country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291713.html|title=Russia's actions prove need for NATO expansion \u2013 Poroshenko|work=Interfax-Ukraine|date=22 September 2015|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408080426/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291713.html|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291691.html|title=Decision on referendum regarding Ukraine's membership in NATO to be made after reforms \u2013 Poroshenko|work=Interfax-Ukraine|date=22 September 2015|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408100326/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291691.html|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291686.html|title=Ukraine-NATO cooperation is crucially important for global security due to Russian aggression \u2013 Poroshenko|work=Interfax-Ukraine|date=22 September 2015|accessdate=30 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408105433/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/291686.html|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2017, in an interview with [[Funke Mediengruppe]], Poroshenko announced he was planning a referendum on whether Ukraine should join NATO.<ref name=\"AJ2217B\">[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/nato-calls-russia-stop-violence-ukraine-170202054257166.html NATO calls on Russia to stop violence in Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224221639/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/nato-calls-russia-stop-violence-ukraine-170202054257166.html |date=24 February 2017 }}, [[Al Jazeera]] (2 February 2017)</ref>\n\n====International====\nPoroshenko was criticized by [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] for signing a decree which banned 41 international journalists and bloggers from entering Ukraine for one year, being labeled as threats to national security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2015/09/ukraine-bans-41-international-journalists-and-blog.php|title=Ukraine bans 41 international journalists and bloggers|work=CPJ|date=16 September 2015|accessdate=10 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113164920/https://cpj.org/2015/09/ukraine-bans-41-international-journalists-and-blog.php|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The list includes three [[BBC]] journalists, and two Spanish journalists currently missing in [[Syria]], all of whom previously covered the Ukraine crisis.<ref>{{cite news|author=Umberto Bacchi|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ukraine-bbc-boss-slams-shameful-ban-international-journalists-1520086|title=Ukraine: BBC boss slams 'shameful' ban on international journalists|newspaper=International Business Times|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=10 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304130055/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ukraine-bbc-boss-slams-shameful-ban-international-journalists-1520086|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Poroshenko visited the Kazakh capital of [[Astana]], during which he told President [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] that his country was the Ukraine's \"window to Asia\" and vise versa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/amp/rubric-polytics/1895612-poroshenko-kazakhstan-is-window-to-asia-for-ukraine-while-ukraine-is-window-to-europe-for-kazakhstan.html|title=Poroshenko: Kazakhstan is \u2018window to Asia' for Ukraine, while Ukraine is \u2018window to Europe\u2019 for Kazakhstan|website=www.ukrinform.net|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> During a visit to [[Gomel, Belarus]] in October 2018, he spoke to the Ukrainian community on the situation in Ukraine, saying that he does \"not want Russia to use Belarus to get to our flank\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uawire.org/poroshenko-we-do-not-want-russia-to-attack-us-through-belarus|title=Ukrainian President: we do not want Russia to attack us through Belarus|last=|first=|date=|website=UAWire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Political career after losing 2019 Presidential election==\nIn the July [[2019 Ukrainian parliamentary election]], Poroshenko is placed first on the party list of [[European Solidarity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/06/9/7217580/|title=\u0414\u0435\u0441\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0456\u0457 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430: \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0456\u0439, \u0413\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0414\u0436\u0435\u043c\u0456\u043b\u0454\u0432|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430}}</ref>\n\n===Law enforcers' raid at Poroshenko's headquarters and gym===\nOn 20 December 2019 the law enforcers raided both [[European Solidarity|Poroshenko\u2019s party]] headquarters and gym. Hidden cameras and recording devices were found inside the gym\u2019s smoke detectors and security alarms. According to the State Investigation Bureau those were allegedly secretly recording and filming Poroshenko's gym clients, of which are politicians and businessmen. Poroshenko and [[Ihor Kononenko]], deputy head of Poroshenko's party, are both owners of said gym and could not be reached for comment. The raid was part of two ongoing criminal investigations which are focused on two concerns. First, the alleged theft of servers with [[classified information]]. Second, the alleged [[tax evasion]] and [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/law-enforcers-search-poroshenkos-party-headquarters-and-gym.html|title=Law enforcers search Poroshenko\u2019s party headquarters and gym|last=Sorokin|first=Oleksiy|date=2019-12-21|website=[[KyivPost]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200104231421/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/law-enforcers-search-poroshenkos-party-headquarters-and-gym.html?cn-reloaded=1|archive-date=2020-01-04|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Panama Papers==\n{{Main|Panama Papers|List of people named in the Panama Papers}}\nPoroshenko set up an [[offshore company]] in the British Virgin Islands during the peak of the [[war in Donbass]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Pavel|last1=Polityuk|first2=Alessandra|last2=Prentice|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-panama-tax-ukraine-idUSKCN0X1158|title=Ukraine's Poroshenko defends record after Panama leaks|work=Reuters|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=7 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407085008/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-panama-tax-ukraine-idUSKCN0X1158|archivedate=7 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leaked documents from the Panama Papers show that Poroshenko registered the company, Prime Asset Partners Ltd, on 21 August 2014. Records in Cyprus show him as the firm's only shareholder.<ref name=\"Guardian 4 Apr 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/apr/04/panama-papers-ukraine-petro-poroshenko-secret-offshore-firm-russia|title=Ukraine's leader set up secret offshore firm as battle raged with Russia|work=Guardian|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=7 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407003306/http://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/apr/04/panama-papers-ukraine-petro-poroshenko-secret-offshore-firm-russia|archivedate=7 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said that he had done nothing wrong, and the legal firm, Avellum, overseeing the sale of [[Roshen]], Poroshenko's confectionery company, said that \"any allegations of tax evasion are groundless\". The anti-corruption group [[Transparency International]] believes that the \"creation of businesses while serving as president is a direct violation of the constitution\".<ref name=\"BBC News 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-35958762|title=Panama Papers: Ukraine President Poroshenko denies tax claims|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis name was cited in [[List of people and organisations named in the Paradise Papers|the list of politicians named in]] \"[[Paradise Papers]]\" allegations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icij.org/investigations/paradise-papers/explore-politicians-paradise-papers/|title=Explore The Politicians in the Paradise Papers \u2013 ICIJ|work=ICIJ|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:The President's family on the 27th anniversary of Ukraine's Independence - 2018.jpg|thumb|[[Maryna Poroshenko]] (in blue) with some of the couple's children on Ukraine's 27th Independence day]]\nPoroshenko has been married to [[Maryna Poroshenko|Maryna]] since 1984.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\">{{cite web|author1=Tadeusz A. Olsza\u0144ski|author2=Agata Wierzbowska-Miazga|url=http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/analyses/2014-05-28/poroshenko-president-ukraine|title=Poroshenko, President of Ukraine|publisher=OSW, Poland|date=28 May 2014|accessdate=10 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308061143/http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/analyses/2014-05-28/poroshenko-president-ukraine|archivedate=8 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The couple have four children: [[Olexiy Poroshenko|Olexiy]] (born 1985), the twins Yevheniya and Oleksandra (born 2000) and Mykhailo (born 2001).<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> [[Olexiy Poroshenko|Olexiy]] was a representative in the regional parliament of [[Vinnytsia Oblast]].<ref name=PpofileSO/> In November 2014, he became People's Deputy of Ukraine.<ref name=\"sputniknews\">{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/politics/201410281014054950/|author=Sputnik|publisher=sputniknews.com|title=Poroshenko's Son Becomes Ukrainian Parliament Member: Election Commission|accessdate=2016-12-13|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220123907/https://sputniknews.com/politics/201410281014054950/|archivedate=20 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Maryna Poroshenko is a cardiologist, who does not take part in public life, apart from her participation in the activities of the Petro Poroshenko Charity Foundation.<ref name=\"Poroshenko family\"/> Poroshenko became a grandfather on the day of his presidential inauguration of 7 June 2014.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u0434\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c|trans-title=Poroshenko has become a grandfather|newspaper=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028425/|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=7 June 2014|language=uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608032422/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/06/7/7028425/|archivedate=8 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Unification council of Orthodox Church in Ukraine 128.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko, [[Epiphanius I (Metropolitan of Kiev)|Metropolitan Epiphanius]] and [[Andriy Parubiy]] after the [[Unification council of the Orthodox churches of Ukraine|unification council]] of the [[Orthodox Church of Ukraine]] on 15 December 2018]]\nPoroshenko is a member of the [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Kiev Patriarchate)|Ukrainian Orthodox Church]].<ref name=PoroGUOCKP/><ref name=PpofileSO/> Poroshenko has financed the restoration of its buildings and monasteries.<ref name=\"PoroGUOCKP\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/23/petro-poroshenko-heads-landslide-ukraine-election |title=Chocolate tycoon heads for landslide victory in Ukraine presidential election |author=Luke Harding and Oksana Grytsenko |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609171626/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/23/petro-poroshenko-heads-landslide-ukraine-election |archivedate=9 June 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/46136 |title=The Return of the Prodigal Son, Who Never Left Home |publisher=[[The Ukrainian Week]] |date=30 March 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030002842/http://ukrainianweek.com/Politics/46136 |archivedate=30 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.day.kiev.ua/en/article/society/who-will-lead-ukrainian-orthodox-church-moscow-patriarchate-and-where |title=Who will lead Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate) and where? |newspaper=[[Den (newspaper)|Den]] |date=27 February 2014 |accessdate=17 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228063016/http://www.day.kiev.ua/en/article/society/who-will-lead-ukrainian-orthodox-church-moscow-patriarchate-and-where |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In high-level meetings he is often seen with a [[crucifix]].<ref name=PoroGUOCKP/>\n\nPoroshenko speaks fluent [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Russian Language|Russian]], [[English Language|English]] and [[Romanian language|Romanian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-international-18382147-video-petro-poroshenko-discurs-limba-romana-cernauti.htm#self|title=Petro Poroshenko, discurs in limba romana la Cernauti|publisher=[[Hotnews.ro]]|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nPetro Poroshenko is [[diabetes|diabetic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/articles/who-does-putin-want-as-ukrainian-president-32765|title=Who Does Putin Want as Ukrainian President?|publisher=|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural and political image==\n[[File:Petro Poroshenko addresses Euromaidan.jpg|thumb|Poroshenko on stage speaking to [[Euromaidan]] protesters on 8 December 2013.]]\n\nPoroshenko has been nicknamed \"Chocolate King\" because of his ownership of a [[Roshen|large confectionery business]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile Poroshenko\"/> Poroshenko objected to being called an [[Business oligarch|oligarch]], stating that \"Oligarchs are people who seek power in order to further enrich themselves. But I have long fought against bandits who are robbing our country and have destroyed free enterprise\".<ref name=PpofileSO/>\n\nAfter promising during his election campaign to sell his business assets when elected as the [[president of Ukraine]], according to Poroshenko and [[N M Rothschild & Sons|Rothschild Wealth Management & Trust]], since becoming President of Ukraine, he has relinquished the management of his businesses, ultimately (in January 2016) to a [[blind trust]].<ref name=KPp71016/><ref name=\"Pbt20117b\"/>\n\n===Potential implementation of martial law===\nDuring his speeches Petro Poroshenko on numerous occasions has called [[war in Donbass|the war in East Ukraine]] a \"Patriotic War\",<ref>[https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/08/24/7035656/ Poroshenko: this war will enter the history as patriotic (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u0426\u044f \u0432\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0430 \u0443\u0432\u0456\u0439\u0434\u0435 \u0432 \u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u044e \u044f\u043a \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044f\u043d\u0430)]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 24 August 2014</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20141006160959/https://tvi.ua/new/2014/10/04/sohodni_v_ukrayini_yde_vitchyznyana_viyna_2014_roku___poroshenko_video Today in Ukraine takes place the 2014 Patriotic War, \u2013 Poroshenko (\u0421\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456 \u0439\u0434\u0435 \u0432\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044f\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0430 2014 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443, \u2013 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e)]. TVi. 4 October 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.radiosvoboda.org/a/26661001.html Poroshenko: I believe in a victory of the 2014 Patriotic War (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u0432\u0456\u0440\u044e \u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0443 \u0443 \u0412\u0456\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044f\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0456 2014 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443)]. [[Radio Liberty]]. 28 October 2014</ref> yet did not initiate implementation of martial law, for which he was criticized on numerous occasions by politicians and the general public.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/politics/2014/08/140828_experts_on_martial_law_vs Is there a need to implement a martial law? (\u0427\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d?)] [[BBC]] Ukraine. 28 August 2014</ref><ref>[http://vgolos.com.ua/news/maydan_ta_batalyony_vymagayut_vid_poroshenka_zaprovadyty_voiennyy_stan_na_donbasi_149795.html Maidan and battalions are requesting for Poroshenko to implement martial law in Donbas (\u041c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0433\u0430\u044e\u0442\u044c \u0432\u0456\u0434 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0456)]. Vgolos. 29 June 2014</ref> Poroshenko noted that it is necessary to realize the consequences of martial law for the country:\n* it will restrict the supply of weaponry and items of dual assignment;\n* the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] won't provide funds to countries that are in war.<ref>[http://uapress.info/uk/news/show/32050 Poroshenko explained why cannot implement martial law (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043f\u043e\u044f\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0432, \u0447\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d)]. UApress. 23 July 2014</ref>\n\nA month later the last statement was refuted by a head of the IMF Ukrainian branch Jerome Vacher, \"As for the possible introduction of martial law, the IMF has no formal legal restrictions that impede continuation of mutual cooperation under such conditions. We have already worked with a number of countries where war conflicts of various intensity unfolded\".<ref>[https://ukr.media/ukrain/214620/ IMF will continue support for Ukraine in case of introduction of martial law (\u041c\u0412\u0424 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0436\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0443 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0456 \u0432\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0443)]. Ukr.media. 29 October 2014</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2015, in his interview with the Spanish [[El Pais]], Poroshenko stated that he will introduce martial law in the case of an escalation of the situation in Donbas, but that that decision will limit democracy and liberties as well as threaten the development of the economy.<ref>[https://lb.ua/news/2015/02/05/294580_poroshenko_obyavit_voennoe_polozhenie.html (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u0442 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0430)]. LB.ua. 5 February 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/02/5/7057583/ Poroshenko: if conflict will expand, there may be a martial law across whole country (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u042f\u043a\u0449\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0435, \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0431\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d \u043f\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0456\u0439 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456)]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 5 February 2015</ref>\n\nMartial law in Ukraine [[Martial law in Ukraine|was introduced]] for 30 days in late November 2018, after the [[Kerch Strait incident]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46684602 Martial laws comes to an end in Ukraine after 30 days], [[BBC News]] (26 December 2018)</ref>\n\n===Connections with Dmytro Firtash===\nIn April 2015, Ukrainian oligarch [[Dmytro Firtash]] at a court session about his extradition to the United States stated that at the [[2014 Ukrainian presidential election|Ukrainian presidential election]] he financially supported Poroshenko,<ref name=\"fwgpaap\">[https://zn.ua/POLITICS/firtash-my-poluchili-poroshenko-prezidentom-klichko-merom-kak-i-hoteli-174844_.html Firtash: We got Poroshenko as a president, Klychko as a mayor as we all wanted (\u0424\u0438\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0448: \u041c\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c, \u041a\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e \u2013 \u043c\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043c, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0438 \u0445\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438)]. [[Mirror Weekly]]. 30 April 2015</ref> and [[Vitali Klitchko]] in the Kiev city mayoral election.<ref name=fwgpaap/>\n\n===Mikheil Saakashvili===\n{{main|Mikheil Saakashvili#Stripping of Ukrainian citizenship}}\n[[File:Impeachment March (Kiev; 2017-12-03) 03.jpg|thumb|Saakashvili-led protesters demand Poroshenko's impeachment, Kiev, 3 December 2017]]\nOn 29 May 2015, Poroshenko invited former [[President of Georgia]] and his friend [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] to help with conducting reforms in the Ukraine and granted him Ukrainian citizenship.<ref>Poroshenko, P. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150602040433/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/19531.html \"About granting a Ukrainian citizenship to Saakashvili M. as a person granting whom the citizenship of Ukraine poses a state interest for Ukraine (\u041f\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u044f\u0442\u0442\u044f \u0434\u043e \u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0448\u0432\u0456\u043b\u0456 \u041c. \u044f\u043a \u043e\u0441\u043e\u0431\u0438, \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u044f\u0442\u0442\u044f \u044f\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u0434\u043e \u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0456\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438)\"]. Presidential ukase \u2116 301/2015. 29 May 2015</ref> The very next day after receiving citizenship on 30 May 2015, Saakashvili was appointed by the president as head (governor) of the Odessa Regional State Administration (see [[Governor of Odessa Oblast]]).<ref>Poroshenko, P. ''About appointment of M.Saakashvili as a head of Odessa Oblast State Administration''. Presidential ukase \u2116 304/2015. 30 May 2015</ref> However, on 26 July 2017 Poroshenko issued a decree{{#tag:ref|The decree was not made publicly available \"in accordance with the legislation on personal data protection\".<ref>[https://www.unian.info/politics/2051641-decree-on-stripping-saakashvili-of-ukraine-citizenship-not-to-be-published-bankova.html Decree on stripping Saakashvili of Ukraine citizenship not to be published \u2013 Bankova], [[UNIAN:]] (27 July 2017)</ref>|group=nb}} stripping Saakashvili of his [[Ukrainian citizenship]], without providing any reason. According to ''[[The Economist]]'', most observers saw Poroshenko's stripping Saakashvili of his citizenship \"simply as the sidelining of a political rival\" (Saakashvili started a political party [[Movement of New Forces]] to participate in [[2019 Ukrainian parliamentary election|upcoming elections]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Ukraine strips one of its president's rivals of his citizenship|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21725681-mikheil-saakashvili-former-georgian-president-had-become-threat-power-petro|accessdate=29 July 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=28 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\n===New year vacationing (2018)===\nIn January 2018, journalists from [[Radio Free Europe]] reported that during Poroshenko's New Year's vacation starting 1 January 2018 on the [[Maldives]], there were ten people who spent $500,000 to rent separate islands and the most expensive hotel in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiosvoboda.org/a/news-schemes/28983638.html|title=Mr. Petro Incognito. \u0422\u0430\u0454\u043c\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 (\u0440\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f)|last=|first=|date=|website=\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0456\u043e \u0421\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u0430|language=uk|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"ua.interfax.com.ua\">{{Cite news|url=http://ua.interfax.com.ua/news/general/477347.html|script-title=uk:\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0456 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u0432 \u0443 \u041a\u0438\u0454\u0432\u0456, \u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443 \u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0434\u0456\u0432\u0430\u0445|access-date=2018-04-06|language=uk}}</ref> On 30 March 2018, Poroshenko submitted his income declaration. Poroshenko declared that he spent between 1.3 and 1.4 million UAH on this vacation \u2013 two times less than journalists had reported (some details about the president's vacation were classified).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://public.nazk.gov.ua/declaration/c9e4d7dd-d6b7-44b8-9e26-12e756d36e04|title=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0433\u043b\u044f\u0434 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0457 {{!}} \u0404\u0414\u0418\u041d\u0418\u0419 \u0414\u0415\u0420\u0416\u0410\u0412\u041d\u0418\u0419 \u0420\u0415\u0404\u0421\u0422\u0420 \u0414\u0415\u041a\u041b\u0410\u0420\u0410\u0426\u0406\u0419|website=public.nazk.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"ua.interfax.com.ua\"/>\n\n===Awards===\n* {{flag|Ukraine}} : [[Order of Merit (Ukraine)|Order of Merit]]\n* {{flag|Moldova}} : [[Order of the Republic (Moldova)|Order of the Republic]]\n* {{flag|Poland}} : [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n* {{flag|Spain}} : [[Order of Civil Merit]]\n* {{flag|Ukraine}} : Medal of winner of Ukraine State Prize in Science and Technology\n* {{flag|Saudi Arabia}} : [[Order of King Abdulaziz]]<ref>[http://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1683377#1683377 Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques and President of Ukraine Attend Signing Ceremony of Draft Cooperation Program and Memoranda of Understanding between the Two Countries], Saudi Press Agency.</ref>\n* {{flag|Lithuania}} : Grand Cross of the [[Order of Vytautas the Great]]\n*[[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarchate]]: cross of Panagia Pammakaristos (5 January 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/prezident-vruchiv-visoku-derzhavnu-nagorodu-vselenskomu-patr-52370|title=President presented a high state award to Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew|last=|first=|date=5 January 2019|website=Official website of the President of Ukraine|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n*[[Orthodox Church of Ukraine]]: Order of St. Andrew Pervozvannyi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risu.org.ua/ua/index/all_news/state/church_state_relations/74242/|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0456\u0430\u0440\u0445 \u0424\u0456\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e\u043c|last=|first=|date=10 January 2019|website=risu.org.ua|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.ua/rubric-society/2616822-filaret-vruciv-porosenku-orden-andria-pervozvannogo.html|script-title=uk:\u0424\u0456\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u0440\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0443 \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0456\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e|last=|first=|date=10 January 2019|website=www.ukrinform.ua|language=uk|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> (Pervozvannyi meaning \"[[Andrew the First-Called|The First-Called]]\")\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rudy Giuliani]]\n*[[Lev Parnas and Igor Fruman]]\n*[[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.president.gov.ua/en/ Official website for the President of Ukraine]\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.poroshenko.com.ua/ |title=Personal website |access-date=8 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202133109/http://www.poroshenko.com.ua/ |archive-date=2 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all |language=uk}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160301000652/http://midwestdiplomacy.com/2014/01/24/frozen-revolution-in-ukraine/ Euromaidan Overview]\n*{{C-SPAN|Petro Poroshenko}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Volodymyr Khandohiy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Ukraine)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kostyantyn Gryshchenko]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andriy Klyuyev]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Economic Development and Trade (Ukraine)|Minister of Trade and Economic Development]]|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ihor Prasolov]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Oleksandr Turchynov]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Ukraine]]|years=2014\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Volodymyr Zelensky]]<br />}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Bohdan, Ben, \"[http://euromaidanpress.com/2019/04/19/five-years-of-ukraine-poroshenko-main-achievements-and-failures/ Five years of Poroshenko\u2019s presidency: main achievements and failures \"], 19 April 2019, ''[[Euromaidan Press]].''\n{{Petro Poroshenko}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n{{Presidents of Ukraine}}\n{{Presidency of Ukraine}}\n{{Foreign Ministers of Ukraine}}\n{{Economics ministers of Ukraine}}\n{{National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine}}\n{{Navbox\n|name = First gov